<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / International Company News: Noranda overcomes volatile metal
markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A WEAKER Canadian dollar and lower costs helped Noranda, the Toronto-based
resources group, overcome volatile commodity markets in the third quarter.
The company cautioned that recovery in its businesses was continuing only at
a very slow pace. Zinc prices, which contributed substantially to higher
metals earnings in the third quarter, have moved down sharply in recent
weeks.
Net earnings were CDollars 26m, (USDollars 21m) or six cents a share,
compared with a CDollars 57m loss a year earlier, equivalent to a loss of 39
cents a share. Revenues climbed to CDollars 2.18bn from CDollars 2bn, and
interest charges fell to CDollars 85m from CDollars 105m.
Cash flow from operations almost tripled in the third quarter to CDollars
284m, but long-term debt climbed to CDollars 4.8bn on Sept 30 from CDollars
4.5bn a year earlier.
Earnings from mining and metals rose to CDollars 48m from CDollars 7m,
largely due to a more favourable currency, the healthier zinc market and
productivity improvements.
Forestry earnings were CDollars 6m, compared with a CDollars 20m loss. While
demand for lumber, panelboard and paperboard has strengthened, prices for
pulp, newsprint and most other types of paper remain below levels a year
ago.
</TEXT>
