<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / International Company News: Argentina sells 80% of
state-owned steel mill
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ARGENTINA has privatised its largest state-owned steel mill, selling 80 per
cent of Aceros Parana to a consortium led by Techint, an Argentine
industrial conglomerate for Dollars 409m.
Techint, the only company to bid for Aceros Parana, is one of Argentina's
largest industrial groups and owner of the Siderca and Propulsora specialty
steel companies. It bought Aceros Parana, previously called Somisa, in
alliance with Usiminas and Companhia Vale do Rio Doce of Brazil and Chile's
CAP.
The buyers offered Dollars 140m in cash, plus Dollars 12.1m in foreign debt
certificates, which trade at half their face value.
They are to spend a further Dollars 12.6m to comply with Argentina's rigid
labour laws which force them to sack and re-hire Aceros Parana's 5,800
employees. Furthermore, the buyers must take on Dollars 250m in financial
and contractual liabilities.
Aceros Parana suffered large losses in 1991, when sales of about Dollars
500m were outstripped by losses of Dollars 570m. The buyers expect it to
move into the black in 1995 with a Dollars 37m profit.
Techint - which is injecting Dollars 50m into the venture - is likely to own
30 per cent of the new group, while Usiminas is expected to hold 5 per cent.
</TEXT>
