<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / International Company News: Bristol-Myers to reduce
workforce by 2,280
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRISTOL-Myers Squibb, the world's third biggest pharmaceuticals company,
yesterday said it was cutting its work-force by about 6 per cent, or 2,280
people, in yet another move to improve its position in an increasingly
competitive industry.
In a letter to employees, Mr Wayne Davidson, president, said: 'Health care
cost-containment issues, rebates and restrictions on our ability to market
our products are increasingly affecting the business worldwide. These trends
are expected to continue and, therefore, they need to be addressed on a
sound and sustainable basis.'
Bristol-Myers is also responding to the increasing pressures of price
increase curbs and generic competition which are starting to change the face
of the pharmaceuticals industry.
Earlier this week, the company announced the sale of its Drackett household
products business for Dollars 1.15bn in cash as Bristol moved to concentrate
on its core pharmaceuticals business.
The company's results have been disappointing this year, with profits growth
of only 5 per cent in the first nine months compared with its usual 15 per
cent growth rate.
According to Mr Viren Mehta, partner at Mehta and Isaly in New York, 'all of
the prudent managers in the industry are recognising that the largest market
in the world is not as profitable as it once was. Even companies that are
highly successful have wage freezes, travel and hiring controls and a
greater focus on research. Because of the additional problems that Bristol
has faced and the impact on its share price, management has been motivated
to be more visible with some of the cost controls they are implementing.'
On Wall Street, shares in Bristol-Myers added Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 67 1/4
. The stock has traded as high as Dollars 90 1/8 this year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
