FT  30 OCT 92 / World Commodities Prices: Market Report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONON Metal Exchange COPPER prices continued to stall at overhead resistance
above the Dollars 2,300 a tonne level, and ended with pared gains yesterday.
In sterling terms the cash position closed Pounds 22 higher at Pounds 1,450
a tonne, but some Pounds 7 of the rise reflected the pound's further fall
against the dollar. Dealers said copper's bounce from early lows around
Dollars 2,280 a tonne indicated that the technical picture was becoming
constructive, although upside targets around Dollars 2,315-Dollars 2,320
needed to be cleared to sustain advances. Other LME metals were relatively
quiet, although ALUMINIUM briefly moved back above the Dollars 1,180 a tonne
level for three months delivery. It quickly ran into overhead selling,
however, and subsided to close just Dollars 3.50 up at Dollars 1,176.50 a
tonne. At the London Futures and Options Exchange COCOA prices extended
Wednesday's downturn on lack of buying interest, compounded by a New York
opening below key chart support. The March position ended Pounds 8 down at
Pounds 710 a tonne.
Compiled from Reuters
