<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / Bush and Clinton trade insults as president narrows poll gap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ALL PRETENSIONS to politeness in the US presidential campaign are now in
tatters. Governor Bill Clinton and President George Bush are directly
trading charges that each is unworthy of the public trust, while Mr Ross
Perot continues to belittle both as incapable of leading the country.
The heat is being generated against the background of fresh public opinion
polls which agree that Mr Bush is narrowing the gap but differ wildly on by
how much. Surveys out in the past 24 hours put Mr Clinton ahead by as much
as 10 points (the Washington Post) and as little as 3 points in the latest
CNN/USA Today poll released last night. Most also found Mr Perot was no
longer on the rise.
The big change has been in Mr Clinton's approach towards Mr Bush. Yesterday
in Toledo, Ohio, he angrily charged that 'the American people must see him
for what he is - a desperate person who just wants to hold on to power and
doesn't give a rip about them'.
Though Mr Clinton continues to pound away with his economic message, it is
now thoroughly mixed with assaults on Mr Bush's character. This amounts to a
tactical shift brought about by relentless personal attacks by the
president.
Yesterday, in Michigan, Mr Bush himself shifted tack, perhaps concluding
that he had drawn enough blood for the moment with his disparagement of the
characters of Mr Clinton and Senator Al Gore. Instead, he returned again to
his great encouragement of the week, the improvement in economic output in
the third quarter. Mr Clinton, he charged, had no understanding of the
global economy, did not appreciate that the US was outperforming its rivals
and would put recovery at risk.
In a rare appearance on the campaign trail in Denver on Wednesday night, Mr
Perot attacked the other candidates indiscriminately. He ridiculed Mr
Clinton because the principal business of the governor's state of Arkansas
was raising chickens - 'and these are not jobs which will pass on the
American dream to our children'.
Mr Bush's attitude, he said, was that, 'if you don't do anything, things
will work out'. He urged a crowd of enthusiasts to 'vote your conscience and
confound the pollsters and media'.
