<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / Britain's top 10 forecasters: The FT ranks the performance
of leading economists during the recession
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
1 - Paul Turnbull
UK economist
Smith New Court
Has closely monitored the housing boom and subsequent slump. Long-term term
opponent of UK membership of exchange rate mechanism; wrote in October 1990,
three weeks after Britain joined, of 'dominant risk' of base rates being
kept high due to ERM constraint. Little known outside City, where he has
worked for nearly 15 years. Has few fans in the Treasury. Two months ago had
chance to explain his often trenchant views to Alan Budd, Treasury chief
economic adviser, over private lunch, the first meeting between the two.
2 - Leo Doyle
econometrician
Kleinwort Benson
Computer wizard-cum-economist whose job prior to joining Kleinwort
investment group was a floor cleaner in a psychiatric hospital in Sussex.
Kleinwort's forecasts use a computerised economic model devised by Doyle.
Based on Treasury software, the model takes in extra data on company debts
and housing market. Stays in the background at Kleinwort, where recently
arrived Peter Spencer is chief economist and David Owen the main UK
economist. Surprisingly, the Treasury has yet to contact him about his
model.
3 - Keith Wade
chief economist
Schroders
Low-profile economist whose views are little circulated outside circle of
Schroders' clients. Has worked on UK economy at Schroders for past four
years, initially with Schroders' former chief economist Donald Franklin -
now at Treasury where he works not on forecasts but financial services
regulation. Wrote with Franklin in autumn of 1990 of danger of global
economic slowdown and sugested chancellor 'may have left it too late to
prevent a prolonged recession'. Worked with Alan Budd when they were both at
London Business School.
4 - Patrick Minford
economics professor
Liverpool University
Vehemently anti-ERM and free-market economist. Long disregarded in Treasury
for what have been held to be unsound views. Leading member of 'Liverpool
Six' group of monetarist economists arguing since early 1991 that recession
would be protracted. Says Treasury should have taken more notice early on of
impact of high real interest rates. Wrote - one month after Britain joined
ERM - that devaluation 'seemed inevitable'. Now says 'the Treasury should
come clean and admit it made a hash of things'.
5 - Peter Warburton
UK economist
Robert Fleming
Deep thinker, another member of Liverpool Six group, has been extremely
gloomy about economy since 1990, arguing that weak balance sheets of
companies and large consumer debts would impede growth. On good terms with
Alan Budd; both worked at London Business School. Stopped using computer
models of economy three years ago on ground that they gave wrong results.
Thinks Treasury is too enclosed. Wrote in October 1990 that the economy was
'hamstrung' because of corporate and consumer overborrowing.
6 - Richard Freeman
chief economist
ICI
Outgoing Australian, worked in Treasury before joining Britain's biggest
manufacturing company. Good contacts in industry, receives up-to-the-minute
information on sales and prospects in all ICI divisions, ranging from paints
to fertiliser. Forecasts not widely circulated, writes detailed report every
month on world economy to ICI board. Told ICI directors two years ago of
'big risk' of world recession. Generally gloomy about international outlook
ever since. Key member of informal Treasury panel advising government
forecasters about demand in industry.
7 - Gavyn Davies
chief UK economist
Goldman Sachs
On most counts, Britain's best known economist. Was sounded out last year by
Mr Lamont for post of Treasury chief economic adviser; decided against a
move. With colleague David Walton, quick to change Goldman's monthly
forecasts. Not immune to mistakes: incorrectly predicted recovery a year
ago. Thinks criticism of Treasury has been overdone. He says: 'If I was to
choose two people I would rely on for giving policy advice on the economy
then Terry Burns (Treasury permanent secretary) and Alan Budd would be very
high on my list.'
8 - Tim Congdon
head of Lombard Street Research
Sometimes irrascible but respected monetarist with good track record in
recent years in predicting economic slowdown. Another member of Liverpool
Six, runs his own research group. Wrote in January 1991 of 'nightmarish'
future for Britain with 'severe recession' made worse by ERM constraints.
Says top Treasury officials 'have had too many chances' over wrong economic
decisions and would like to see fresh blood. Thinks Treasury team of Burns
and Budd in particular failed to draw lessons from previous boom-bust
episodes.
8 - Michael Saunders
UK economist
Salomon Brothers
Up and coming, youthful City star, more original than most economists and
particularly good with figures on public-sector borrowing. Poached by
Salomon from gilts broker Greenwell Montagu two years ago. Has warned for
past year of long slowdown. Said two years ago that economy would continue
to weaken during 1991, 'with little prospect of rapid turnround' due to high
real interest rates across Europe and substantial cuts in stocks and fixed
investment. Says that government PSBR forecasts are over-optimistic.
10 - Bill Martin
chief UK economist
UBS Phillips and Drew
Feisty self-publicist; fourth member of Liverpool Six to make the FT's Top
10; the other two, Alan Walters and Gordon Pepper, do not make formal
forecasts. Fierce opponent of ERM; views little taken into account by
Treasury. Has called Treasury projections 'moonshine'. Warned in November
1990 of dangers of 'deepening recession and further political trauma'
arising out of high interest rates and a slide in sterling. Said two years
ago that the government's promise of 'pain first, pleasure later (as a
result of ERM entry) appears impossibly optimistic'.
</TEXT>
