<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / Customs spending 'irregular'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEARLY A quarter of the funds allocated to headquarters divisions of Customs
and Excise in a 'people money' scheme to improve the staff working
environment was spent outside the scope of the scheme, a report from the
National Audit Office disclosed yesterday.
From Pounds 305,000 spent in 1991-92 in 11 headquarters divisions, much was
'outside both the terms of the scheme and the ambit of the vote and was
therefore irregular', the NAO concludes.
That included money spent on personal stereos, clothing, contact lenses,
club subscriptions, meals, handbags, 'expensive pens' and personal
organisers. Items were supposed to require prior management approval.
The details come in the National Audit Office report on the 1991-92 revenue
accounts for HM Customs and Excise and the Inland Revenue, which was
released yesterday.
Sir John Bourn, the comptroller and auditor general, said the results of
examinations of the accounts by his staff were 'satisfactory'.
The review of Inland Revenue accounts showed that one division will be
reviewing the accounts of 700 farmers involving suspected widespread cases
of tax evasion involving undeclared cash transactions and secret bank
accounts.
Other Customs and Excise difficulties identified include Pounds 394m of VAT
arrears more than a year old, of which Pounds 178m were more than two years
old in November 1991. Those figures were reduced to Pounds 341m and Pounds
116m respectively by June 1992. No information is available on how far the
reductions represent arrears as opposed to tax written-off.
The NAO says Customs appears to have underestimated the amount of training
and support required to help staff to convert from traditional methods of
control to a systems-based approach. Customs staff identified 652
irregularities totalling Pounds 1.4m on export refunds related to the Common
Agricultural Policy.
</TEXT>
