FT  30 OCT 92 / Cash control criticised at Civil Service catering body
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SERIOUS FINANCIAL irregularities in the Civil Service catering group Forward
were criticised by the National Audit Office, the parliamentary watchdog,
yesterday.
Sir John Bourn, the auditor general, has qualified the group's accounts
because of 'significant failures in financial control and management' which
may have led to the misappropriation of up to Pounds 200,000 from its Pounds
30m turnover.
Forward, with 1,300 employees, is by far the largest provider of catering to
government departments and public bodies. It was converted to a commercial
trading agency last year as a prelude to full privatisation, for which a
date has yet to be fixed.
The irregularities came to light this year, leading the Treasury to suspend
Mr Roy Wheeler, Forward's chief executive, in July.
Discrepancies at the Forward-run restaurant in Marsham Towers, London,
precipitated an investigation that found 'possible malpractice'.
Ernst and Young, the accountancy firm, was commissioned to examine Forward's
operations. Its report - which led to Mr Wheeler's suspension - concluded
that the caterers' financial control was seriously deficient, its management
ineffective, and its balance sheet inadequate and possibly manipulated.
Records were found to have been destroyed, with evidence of fictitious
employees included on the payroll.
Mr Barry Bloxham, Forward's acting chief executive, said the troubles were
being tackled 'urgently'. The organisation is still trading, although it now
faces stiff competition for its contracts, which are subject to competitive
tender.
</TEXT>
