<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / Pollution pledge at risk
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE environment may have to take second place in the government's review of
energy policy, which has been prompted by the recent controversy about coal
pit closures.
Ministers admit that the UK's commitment to reducing harmful emissions,
which was signed by Mr John Major at the Rio summit only last June, is
incompatible with trying to save more of the coal industry.
In common with other EC countries, the UK has pledged to reduce its
emissions of carbon dioxide to 1990 levels by the year 2000. That, though,
was based on the assumption that the power generation industry would
steadily switch from coal to gas.
If the review leads to a new emphasis on coal, environmental regulations
would require heavy investment in desulphurisation and other clean-up
equipment at power stations.
That would not reduce carbon emissions. The result is that coal-fired power
generation would have more costs heaped on it at a time when it needs to cut
costs to become more competitive.
The nuclear power industry, which will be included in the review, took steps
yesterday to highlight its environmental qualifications.
The British Nuclear Forum, which represents nuclear power operators and
suppliers, said the absence of emissions from nuclear power stations made it
a 'natural partner' for coal.
Professor Peter Jones, a consultant to the forum, said a mixture of coal and
nuclear power would leave more room for coal within the emission constraints
than a mix of coal and natural gas, both of which produce carbon dioxide.
The forum's campaign is designed to persuade ministers not to scale down
nuclear power in order to encourage market share for coal. Prof Jones said
the cost of generating electricity from nuclear's long-established stations
where costs had been written down was among the cheapest in the country.
If nuclear was replaced by either coal or gas, that would push up
electricity bills. It would also produce huge plant decommissioning costs
that would have to be absorbed either by the consumer or the taxpayer.
Nevertheless, the view at the Department of Trade and Industry, where the
review is being conducted, is that it will be difficult to save more than a
few collieries and coal jobs.
Although the government has several options for raising coal consumption,
many of them involve government intervention or have undesirable knock-on
effects in other sectors of the energy industry.
DTI sources emphasise that the review is being launched 'with an open mind',
but it will not lead to an increase in the coal market from the 40m tonnes
at present projected to the 60m needed to save large numbers of jobs.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
