<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / Donaldson to chair law panel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LORD DONALDSON, the former master of the rolls, is to chair a new body that
will tackle legal uncertainties affecting the UK wholesale financial
markets.
The financial law panel will comprise up to 12 distinguished lawyers and
market practitioners.
It will help to resolve legal difficulties before they reach the courts;
review proposed legislation and regulations; and make proposals in the
wholesale financial markets, which encompass issues such as foreign exchange
dealings, derivatives and cross-border insolvency.
Formation of the panel is the main recommendation of the legal risk review
committee chaired by Lord Alexander of Weedon, chairman of National
Westminster Bank, which was set up by the Bank of England in April last
year.
The committee was established after the confusion over the legal position of
a number of developments in the financial markets including the
local-authority swaps case.
Lord Alexander said: 'We concluded that the underpinning of the wholesale
financial markets is basically sound. But it is important to minimise
uncertainty if the UK's standing as a pre-eminent international financial
centre is not to be jeopardised.'
The panel will have a chairman and a deputy chairman, up to 10 other
members, and a small secretariat. It will also be able to establish working
and advisory groups. Report of the legal risk review committee. LRRC, New
Change, London EC4M 9AA. Free.
</TEXT>
