FT  30 OCT 92 / Staff revert to trusted radio and telephones
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON Ambulance Service staff have gone back to using paper, telephones and
radios to co-ordinate ambulances after Monday's failure of the new computer
system.
Mr John Wilby, the service's chief executive, resigned on Wednesday after
ambulance staff claimed that up to 20 people died unnecessarily on Monday
because of delays caused by the computer system.
Officers of the National Union of Public Employees, the main union
representing ambulance service staff, say management had been warned
repeatedly that the system was faulty, but employees' objections were
overridden.
Mr Paul Webster, a Nupe branch secretary who works at the ambulance service
headquarters, said: 'We had been telling them for eight or nine months. We
had said all along that it didn't work.'
He blames the escalation of the troubles on a combination of management's
refusal to listen, inadequate training, and political pressure.
The computer system is still operating this week, but once the computer has
allocated a job to an ambulance crew, details are being printed out so that
control room staff can contact ambulance stations and crew directly by
telephone or radio.
'We are using the computer and the paper back-up system so that nothing can
be missed. Calls are not getting lost any more,' said Mr Webster.
Nupe is still not happy about using the 'part and part' system, which has
been in use since March. Mr Chris Humphreys, Nupe regional officer for
London, said: 'It is by no means a secure system. There is still a lot of
risk.'
Mr David Adamthwaite, an ambulance crew member and Nupe senior staff
co-ordinator, says the new system is 'fundamentally flawed'.
'Whatever system you apply, people have to have confidence in it. We want to
go back to the simple system, telephone and radio. Anybody can use it. Crews
have confidence in it.'
</TEXT>
