<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / Parliament and Politics: Confusion over Danish treaty move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRESH ammunition for opponents of the Maastricht treaty came yesterday when
a Foreign Office official admitted that it was unclear what the implications
of accommodating Denmark's objections will be for the treaty's ratification
in other European Community countries.
Mr Michael Jay, a senior Foreign Office official responsible for European
Community policy, told the Commons foreign affairs committee that it was
uncertain what form any deal to help Denmark would take.
He went on: 'Until one is clear what the document that comes out at the end
of it will be, it is very hard to know what the implications will be for
other member states so far as ratification is concerned, or for us.'
Denmark released proposals on Tuesday for ending the deadlock resulting from
its rejection by referendum of Maastricht. The UK government has been
embarrassed by the leaking on Wednesday of a memorandum written by Mr Jay
which warned of 'difficult' negotiations ahead between Denmark and the 11
other EC countries over the plans.
Euro-sceptics and Labour believe ministers cannot claim that the way ahead
for Denmark is clearer and that the government's case for bringing
Maastricht back to the Commons next week has been undermined. Mr James Cran,
Tory MP for Beverley, asked: 'Why is parliament wasting its time on
something which is now hypothetical or at least conditional?'
Mr John Smith, Labour leader, challenged Mr John Major in the Commons over
'undertakings' he gave in September not to proceed with the Maastricht bill
until the terms for Danish ratification, and a clearer definition of
subsidiarity (the principle of decisions being taken at the lowest possible
level) were agreed.
Mr Smith said the Foreign Office document confirmed that the prime minister
'cannot possibly discharge the undertakings' before December's Edinburgh
summit.
The government says there is no question of the Maastricht treaty being
renegotiated. Denmark's identified areas of concern - on defence, internal
justice policy, economic and monetary union, and citizenship - could almost
certainly be resolved without fresh UK legislation, one Whitehall official
said.
In the unlikely event of a separate, free-standing treaty being needed, it
would not impinge on the contents of the Maastricht Bill to be considered by
MPs, he added.
The Commons foreign affairs committee has also been told by Mr Jeremy Lever
QC, a specialist in European law, that provisions in Maastricht on
subsidiarity may prove ineffective in areas such as employment and the
environment without stronger agreement on implementation.
Mr Jay sought to counter such fears with figures showing that the number of
legislative proposals from the European Commission has fallen from 162 in
1990 to 118 proposed during 1992, of which only 48 have actually been
brought forward.
</TEXT>
