<TEXT>
A 'HEADS of agreement' document acceptable to Northern Ireland's political
parties, and the Irish and British governments, is becoming an increasingly
likely outcome of talks taking place on the province's future, Ralph Atkins
writes.
Sir Patrick Mayhew, Northern Ireland secretary, hinted to MPs yesterday that
he believes agreement on such a report is feasible - and probably the best
that can be expected in the week remaining before the talks end.
Bilateral talks between the participants and Sir Ninian Stephen, the
independent chairman, continued yesterday in Belfast. Further meetings are
expected today, with increasing attention being paid to the possibility of
reaching 'heads of agreement'.
Mr James Molyneaux and the Rev Ian Paisley, the two Unionist leaders, have
indicated that they will pull out of the talks about a week before the
November 16 meeting of the Anglo-Irish conference, which marks the formal
close of the talks.
Sir Patrick said he hoped there would be only an 'intermission' before talks
resumed. He told the Commons that he would make a statement when the talks
closed and said that a 'heads of agreement' was 'a practical possibility'.
