<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / World Trade News: Nissan to rationalise distribution in
Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NISSAN, Japan's second largest car maker, expects to make big savings on its
vehicle distribution operations in Europe by scrapping national distribution
centres. From next year, dealers in most continental European markets are to
receive their vehicles directly from one of two much larger distribution
centres, an existing facility in Amsterdam, or a new one being built in
Barcelona and due to begin operations next spring. A third may be added
later.
Under Nissan's traditional system, vehicles have been supplied from its main
import centre in Amsterdam to large compounds, some operated by independent
distributors, in each country, with each country's dealer network drawing on
this national 'pool'. By eliminating the compounds, Nissan expects to make
big inventory savings.
The new system is partly in operation in northern Europe, with dealers in
Germany, northern France, Switzerland and Holland supplied from Amsterdam.
Southern France will be supplied from Barcelona when the centre opens, with
Portugal and Greece brought into the system later.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
