FT  30 OCT 92 / European Court finds Ireland at fault over abortion
information ban
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ireland has been found to have violated human rights for banning two
pregnancy counselling clinics from providing information to women on how and
where to obtain abortions abroad, Tim Coone writes.
The European Court of Human Rights in Strasbourg ruled yesterday that the
1988 ban, ordered by an Irish Supreme Court injunction, had violated a right
to receive and impart information, information which was in any case
available elsewhere from telephone directories or through contacts abroad.
The European Court awarded the two clinics a total of IPounds 194,000
(Pounds 208,000) in costs and damages.
Ireland has a constitutional ban on abortion dating back to 1983.
