FT  30 OCT 92 / Poll may follow Dublin split
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IRELAND faces the possibility of an imminent general election, following the
emergence of apparently irreconcilable differences between the leaders of
the two coalition parties in government.
Last Tuesday, Mr Albert Reynolds, the prime minister, accused Mr Des
O'Malley, his industry minister and leader of the Progressive Democrat (PD)
party, the junior partner in the coalition, of being 'reckless,
irresponsible and dishonest' in giving evidence last June to a parliamentary
inquiry into the country's beef industry.
Mr Reynolds made the accusation during the inquiry, where he has been
defending his record as industry minister during 1987 and 1988, when he
authorised export insurance cover to a number of Irish companies for beef
exports to Iraq.
Mr O'Malley has not responded publicly to the accusation, but his party said
on Wednesday it had 'undermined the effectiveness of the government'.
Yesterday Ms Mary Harney, a PD deputy and a junior minister of state, said
shortly after speaking to Mr O'Malley: 'We cannot now pretend it is business
as usual and that everybody can go into a cabinet room as if nothing has
happened. That would be terribly dishonest and the government in those
circumstances just couldn't be effective.'
Under intense cross-examination yesterday by the counsel for Mr O'Malley at
the beef inquiry, Mr Reynolds stood by his allegation, although he had to be
pressed 10 times by the counsel and was finally instructed by the inquiry
chairman, Mr Justice Liam Hamilton, to 'just answer the question' to
identify exactly what part of Mr O'Malley's evidence he considered
dishonest.
Mr Reynolds said he considered a figure given by Mr O'Malley of a 'potential
liability' to the state of IPounds 170m (Pounds 182m), as a result of Mr
Reynolds' decisions in granting export insurance cover to Iraq, was
dishonest.
Relations between the two coalition partners have deteriorated sharply in
recent weeks, because of differences over the administration of industrial
development policy, and over the wording of an abortion referendum due in
December.
Neither party, however, wishes to be seen as the one which precipitates a
general election, so the political brinkmanship could continue for days or
weeks yet.
</TEXT>
