<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / German inflation figures hit interest rate cut hopes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER and QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FRANKFURT, BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HOPES of a quick and substantial cut in German interest rates receded
yesterday after the publication of consumer price inflation figures for
October which were worse than economists' expectations.
According to a provisional estimate made by the Federal Statistics Office in
Wiesbaden, annual consumer price inflation in October in the western part of
Germany was 3.8 per cent, an increase of 0.4 per cent from September.
Economists were expecting inflation of at most 3.6 per cent, the same as in
September.
The estimate, based on data from the states of Bavaria, Baden-Wurttemberg,
North Rhine-Westphalia and Hesse, defied expectations that the strengthening
of the D-Mark since the currency turbulence of last month would dampen
inflationary pressures. The D-Mark has appreciated by 8 per cent against
leading currencies since the beginning of the year.
The Bundesbank held its fortnightly council meeting yesterday and left its
key Lombard and discount rates unchanged, at 9.5 and 8.25 per cent
respectively.
Although the Bundesbank does not react to a single month's inflation
statistics, the increase means a cut in the internationally sensitive
Lombard rate and the key discount rate would be more difficult to justify,
however intense the pressure grows for further easing in the wake of
deteriorating economic conditions in Germany. This week, Germany's five
leading economic research institutes urged a rapid relaxation of rates and
said the west German economy was in a 'critical state'.
Recent speeches from influential members of the central bank's ruling
council have made clear that fighting inflation is the main objective of
monetary policy. The bank has taken pains to explain that it has reduced
interest rates sharply, in that money market rates have dropped by nearly a
full percentage point since early September.
The fall in money market rates - together with comments playing down the
importance of M3 monetary growth, traditionally one of the central bank's
most important anti-inflation targets - has led to expectations of
substantial rate cuts in coming months. But further cuts will be difficult,
if not impossible, to justify when prices are rising.
The inflation figure was driven up by inflation of 4 per cent in Hesse, by
3.6 per cent in North Rhine-Westphalia, 3.9 per cent in Bavaria and 3.3 per
cent in Baden-Wurttemberg.
The German government's budget deficit for 1993 seems certain to rise by
several billion D-Marks above the forecast DM38bn (Pounds 15.3bn), in spite
of strenuous efforts to find more savings, according to senior officials,
Quentin Peel writes from Bonn.
The partners in the coalition remain clearly divided about the extent to
which drastic cuts in spending must be found, and the extent to which the
deficit can be allowed to rise. The 1993 budget is for DM435.65bn, and the
DM38bn deficit is a slight reduction on this year's DM40bn.
Although all are talking of 'drastic and painful savings', there is no
consensus about where they should be made, or how great they should be.
Chancellor Helmut Kohl himself warned this week: 'There is a gap between
what we say and what we do.' While urging savings, he seemed to warn against
making excessive cuts in the biggest areas of state subsidies - agriculture,
coal mining and shipbuilding.
</TEXT>
