<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / Finns firm for Maastricht
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Mauno Koivisto yesterday said Finland would meet all its
obligations under the Maastricht treaty, including possible participation in
a common European defence force.
In contrast to Denmark's equivocations, including this week's demands for
opt-outs on a common currency and defence force, Mr Koivisto said Finns
intended to be 'honest members' of the European Community.
At the end of his trip to Brussels to talk about pending negotiations on
full EC membership, Mr Koivisto indirectly criticised Denmark for asking for
special treatment. 'It is not easy to say old members have more rights than
new members,' he said.
Mr Koivisto said yesterday that he expected negotiations on EC membership to
begin 'sometime next year'.
During a news conference, Mr Koivisto also hinted at Finnish interest in
joining Nato. He described talks with Mr Manfred Worner, Nato
secretary-general, as 'most interesting' and said Finland wanted to learn
more about the role of Nato and the West European Union (WEU) in Europe's
security.
However, the president stressed it was not 'timely' to discuss possible
Finnish membership of Nato.
</TEXT>
