<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / Major bolsters support among Tory backbenchers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Major significantly bolstered his support on the government's
backbenches last night by condemning internal Tory 'squabbling' over
Maastricht and issuing a powerful defence of his decision to press ahead
with ratification of the treaty.
In a plainly-put yet conciliatory performance that won compliments from all
sections of the party, Mr Major said he would not 'rat' on Britain's
commitment to its European partners to approve the accord.
However, it remains unclear whether the prime minister's personal appeal to
the loyalty of a packed meeting of the 1922 committee will prove enough to
ensure that Wednesday's vote can be won by the government.
Putting his integrity at the centre of the debate, Mr Major referred to the
continuing impasse in international trade talks as grounds for pushing on
with ratification.
'Why should we be able to tell France not to rat on Gatt, if we rat on
Maastricht?' he asked.
'Progress on the Maastricht bill is to build confidence in the economy and
strengthen the credibility and authority of Britain in Europe,' he said,
adding that it was not 'a glorious posture' for the UK to hide behind the
Danes.
His blunt call for the support of party rank and file was said by several
MPs to have re-established his leadership credentials and persuaded a number
of potential opponents in next Wednesday's crucial Maastricht debate to
swing behind him. Hardline Tory Euro-sceptics, however, said they would not
be budged by the appeal.
Mr Major said he would not try to 'ram' the Maastricht bill through the
Commons, stressed the need for party unity and insisted the government's
European policy was 'central' to achieving economic recovery.
Party backing was also vital to the government in tough negotiations to come
with Britain's European partners. 'There is an absolute necessity to remove
the uncertainty of the European issue,' he said. 'Let us put aside the
squabbling and get on with the discussing. We owe it to ourselves and we owe
it to millions.'
Mr Major also pledged that next month's Autumn Statement would include a
package of economic measures that would raise the morale of the Conservative
backbenches. He admitted to having learnt 'a salutary lesson' from the coal
debacle.
His speech came after the cabinet threw down the gauntlet to his
Conservative Euro-sceptic rebels by opting unanimously for a head-on
confrontation over the motion now set to be debated next week.
Earlier the anti-treaty faction claimed that some 60 backbenchers are ready
to defy the leadership and vote against the motion.
Before the meeting, Mr James Cran MP, an unofficial 'whip' for the
Euro-sceptics, warned: 'We are quietly confident that if the government is
not careful it is heading for defeat.'
Lord Tebbit, the former party chairman, also returned to the fray, using a
speech to Henley Young Conservatives to call on the rebels to defeat the
government or force a postponement of ratification until after the Edinburgh
summit in December.
Not too late, Page 10
Joe Rogaly, Page 21
Delors' warning, Page 22
