<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / Smith New Court man tops economic forecasters survey
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S most accurate economic forecaster during the recession is Mr Paul
Turnbull, chief UK economist at stockbroker Smith New Court, according to a
Financial Times survey published today.
The Treasury only manages 19th place out of 41 forecasting groups in the
detailed FT analysis which measures the accuracy of growth projections
during the recession.
The FT's survey coincided with the announcement last night by Mr Norman
Lamont, the chancellor, that he is setting up a panel of independent
forecasters to help with official Treasury projections.
Invitations will go out shortly to people the Treasury would like on the
panel. The Treasury said last night it would look at the FT's survey with
interest.
The FT's assessment, which has taken in more than 3,000 individual
forecasts, is based on records of what individual economists said about the
economy on a monthly basis over the past three years.
It is the most comprehensive effort since the recession started to rank
economists according to accuracy of their growth projections.
While virtually all UK economists - including Mr Turnbull - have been
over-optimistic in their predictions, the Treasury's forecasting record is
significantly worse than that of other groups. Four of the top 10
forecasters are members of the 'Liverpool Six' group of monetarist
economists who warned early last year that the recession would be protracted
and that Britain might have to leave the European exchange rate mechanism.
Organisations at the bottom of the FT's list include City University
Business School, Nomura and Credit Suisse First Boston.
Mr Turnbull, 39, who has worked at Smith New Court since 1986, said
yesterday: 'It's no surprise I have come out top in the survey. My forecasts
have been bloody good.' His latest forecast for 1992 is that the economy
will contract by 1.1 per cent, followed by weak growth of 0.6 per cent next
year.
An outspoken monetarist, Mr Turnbull, said he was delighted Britain had left
the ERM and would like to see interest rates at 6 per cent to help a
recovery. He would also like the government to cut public spending and raise
taxes in next year's Budget to combat the deterioration in public sector
borrowing.
Of the 10 forecasters who have shown the greatest accuracy on growth
forecasts in the recession, five are leading monetarist economists who have
attacked government policies, in particular concerning ERM membership.
How they measured up, Page 14
</TEXT>
