<HEADLINE>
FT  30 OCT 92 / World Trade News: Danish train order for Germany
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HILARY BARNES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   COPENHAGEN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DSB, DENMARK'S state railway company, has placed an initial DKr600m (Pounds
61.7m) order with Linke-Hoffman-Busch/Siemens, a German consortium, for
eight trains for the Copenhagen suburban network.
The consortium now appears likely to provide trains for the whole DKr8bn
order for the network. The opposition Social Democrats had argued the
contracts should go to Denmark's ABB Skandia.
But yesterday, the opposition agreed it would be unable to stop DSB giving
the order to LHB/Siemens without breaking EC public tendering law. The first
trains are to be delivered in 1995. By 1997, DSB will decide whether to
order 120 trains, worth DKr8bn.
The German trains are lighter than ABB Skandia's. DSB says trains supplied
by the German consortium would be more fuel-efficient than Skandia's. But
Skandia claims the choice of new technology in the German trains means the
consortium may be unable to deliver on time.
</TEXT>
