<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / UK Company News: DG Durham suspended on bid talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Stock Exchange yesterday suspended dealings in DG Durham, the insurance
broker, after the company announced that it was in discussions with a
potential buyer.
The USM-quoted shares were suspended at 4p, compared to a 1992 high of 11p,
giving the company a market capitalisation of Pounds 800,000.
'The company has entered discussions which may lead to an offer being made
for the shares of the company and/or to a subscription into its major
operating subsidiaries.'
Durham reported that pre-tax losses came to Pounds 220,000 in the six months
ending June 30 1991.
This compared with pre-tax profits of Pounds 765,000 in 1990.
At the time it said the downturn was due partially to difficult trading
conditions in the travel insurance business, in which it is a market leader.
Its Lloyd's broking subsidiary was sold earlier this year.
A further announcement accompanied by preliminary results for the period to
March 31 1992 will be made 'as soon as possible'.
</TEXT>
