<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / UK Company News: Standards now more complex - The new profit
and loss account requirements
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NEW financial reporting standard on the profit and loss account unveiled
yesterday by the Accounting Standards Board may come as little surprise to
the cognoscenti, but it will make considerable extra demands on both
preparers and users.
Those who have been following the development of FRS 3 will not be surprised
by the new document. In many ways it reflects FRED 1, the consultation
exposure draft issued at the end of last year.
FRS 3 is the culmination of two years work, and is likely to stand for two
years before being revised. It is the ASB's first fully home-grown standard,
since FRS 1 on cash flows was a remnant from its predecessor body, and FRS 2
on consolidated accounts was driven by company legislation.
A number of significant changes have been introduced as a result of the
public consultation - and notably comments from companies. The principal
ones are:
dropping the requirement for disclosure of 'revenue investment' such as
advertising and training expenses
a statement reconciling movements in shareholders' funds, derived from
profit, dividends, other gains and losses, new share capital and goodwill
removing a specific 'exceptional item' category for most elements in favour
of including material, unusual profits or losses in the income or expense
heading to which they relate
retaining as separately disclosed exceptional three items: the costs of a
fundamental reorganisation or restructuring, and profits or losses on
disposal of fixed assets or a business
Meanwhile, many of the changes already mooted in FRED 1 represent important
advances. These include a new financial statement of total recognised gains
and losses, which Tweedie calls a 'world first' which he expects other
accounting standards-setters overseas to follow.
It includes an item on foreign currency translations, the significance of
which many failed to spot in the accounts of Polly Peck International. It
will also be possible to see the effect of property and other asset
revaluations compared with their historic cost with a new note to the
accounts.
Prior knowledge of what was coming does not mean users will be ready for the
changes and able to easily cope with the newly-constituted accounts. That is
part of the ASB's intention.
Mr David Tweedie, the ASB's chairman, is convinced that accounts users are
obsessed with a single number - earnings per share.
By extension - as well as by virtue of the common link between
performance-related pay and earnings - company managements come under
pressure to manipulate that figure.
The thrust of FRS 3 is to replace this 'headline number' with the so-called
'information-set' approach. Readers kept on their toes because they are
forced to pick and choose numbers to find the data on corporate performance
that they seek.
By bringing everything above the line into pre-tax profits, the new earnings
figure will become less stable, predictable or comparable - either between
companies or over time. That will force analysts and others to rely less on
the bottom line figure and come up with their own - different - methods.
'We're saying that if you don't like the way the figures are presented, all
you've got to do is take your pencil out and recalculate,' says Tweedie.
FRS 3 does include some information which was not previously in accounts,
notably splitting out the contribution to results from acquisitions,
continuing and discontinued operations.
Most is already available, but often buried in the notes. The introduction
of the new format should put an end to companies hiding behind 'reserve
accounting' in which changes are concealed to all but the most meticulous.
But that raises a paradox. The new standard is making accounts far more
complex, introducing new notes and statements, and adding additional figures
to the face of the profit and loss account.
Tweedie admits that FRS 3 will not be easy for the 'ordinary user' of
accounts to digest. Yet arguably those who are more qualified are already
able to hunt for concealed numbers; others will be more confused than ever.
An unusual aspect of FRS 3 is the inclusion of a dissenting statement from
one of the nine ASB members, Mr Bob Bradfield of Cazenove, the securities
house. He says disposals should not be above the line because gain or loss
on sale is based on historic case not comparable with trading profits.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 22
</PAGE>
