<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Lamont's chance to set things straight
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH and EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN MR Norman Lamont, the chancellor, rises to deliver the annual Mansion
House speech tonight, he will have an opportunity to restore his tarnished
image in the financial markets. He is also expected to talk about a new
spirit of openness at the Treasury.
Addressing bankers and City representatives Mr Lamont will try to end
confusion about the government's economic policy and dispel the gloom about
the UK economy which has recently knocked the pound and depressed the stock
market.
While he is likely to provide more details about new thinking at the
Treasury, to explain more fully the way in which economic policy is
operated, he is not expected to outline significant initiatives on monetary
policy or changes in the rules for funding the public sector borrowing
requirement.
Nor is he likely to do more than touch briefly on the framework for public
spending over the next few years, or on measures to entice private-sector
cash into infrastructure projects. Both subjects will probably be covered in
detail in his Commons address on November 12, part of the Treasury's Autumn
Statement.
The chancellor's biggest task is to reduce the uncertainty about economic
policy that has emerged in the wake of sterling's exit from the European
exchange rate mechanism on Black Wednesday and recent indications that
Britain's longest recession for 50 years is worsening.
Financial markets have been unsettled by apparent differences in emphasis on
economic policy between Downing Street and the Treasury that have emerged
recently.
While Mr John Major, the prime minister, has talked about Britain putting
economic growth at the top of its policy objectives, the Treasury has
continued to reiterate the government's desire to bear down on inflation and
worry about the level of sterling.
Mr Lamont will try to link the two sets of policy statements, emphasising
that the government's objective remains long-term, stable growth within a
framework of permanently low inflation.
There is a fairly remote possibility that Mr Lamont will announce changes to
the way in which the government's deficit, or the public sector borrowing
requirement, is funded.
The Mansion House speech is almost always preceded by calls for a change in
the funding rule and every year expectations are disappointed. But this
year, says Mr Nigel Richardson, economist at SG Warburg securities, the
arguments for change have become 'more persuasive than ever'.
The full-fund rule requires the authorities to fund the PSBR by sales of
government bonds, or gilts, outside the banking and building societies
sectors.
Since gilts bought by banks or building societies do not count as funding,
the Bank of England has to sell even more gilts to meet the requirements of
the PSBR.
Many economists expect the PSBR to grow to more than Pounds 40bn in the next
financial year. One way of reducing it at a single stroke would be to count
purchases of gilts by banks and building societies as funding. This could
cut next year's PSBR by as much as Pounds 6bn.
As well as easing the funding burden, a break from the full-fund rule could
have other beneficial effects on the economy.
Since the authorities would have to raise less cash from the public, the
supply of money circulating in the economy would be increased. Conversely,
if more gilts were sold to the public than were required to finance the
government's borrowing, money would be soaked up and the economy left less
liquid.
Economists also say that a smaller volume of sales of gilts would raise
prices and lower yields, encouraging investment by companies as it would let
them raise fixed-rate finance more cheaply.
Underfunding the PSBR could also boost equity prices, thereby cheapening the
cost of equity capital and encouraging rights issues.
For all this, the authorities appear reluctant to tinker with the funding
rules.
Mr Roger Bootle, chief economist at Greenwell Montagu, and long an advocate
of underfunding, says: 'There still seems to be a view in the Treasury that
such a move would be pointless.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-10702</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJ2B8AFPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Slight fall in repossessions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOME repossessions in England and Wales fell slightly in the three months to
the end of September, according to figures released yesterday by the Lord
Chancellor's office.
Mr Tony Baldry, housing minister, said the figures showed a 'welcome
decline' and added: 'Mortgage counselling for those in difficulties is now
widespread and shows that lenders want to help people out of their
difficulties.'
The Building Societies Association was more cautious in its welcome for the
figures. It said the fall was caused by a widespread policy of 'forbearance'
by lenders, rather than by any reduction in the scale of mortgage arrears.
The figures do not include voluntary repossessions - where occupants
surrender the keys to their home without a contest - and so are only a
preliminary indication.
In the third quarter of this year 34,474 repossession actions were entered,
down 32 per cent from 51,037 in the same quarter last year, and 30,661
repossession orders were made, 23 per cent down from the corresponding
period last year.
Repossession orders for the first nine months of the year, at 99,592, show a
6 per cent fall from the corresponding period last year.
Shelter, the housing group, urged the Lord Chancellor to recommend that
lenders were not granted possession orders unless debt counselling had been
offered.
It said long-term mortgage arrears had more than doubled by the end of July
compared with the same point last year.
</TEXT>
