<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Argentine exports favoured in policy switch
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ARGENTINA last night announced a sweeping revision of its foreign trade
policies, in the face of recession, a growing trade deficit and rising
political opposition to the government of President Carlos Menem.
To defend local output from foreign competition, Mr Domingo Cavallo, economy
minister, said Argentina will raise 'temporarily', to 10 per cent from 3 per
cent, a flat-rate tax charged on all imports and known as the 'statistics'
duty. 'We are doing this because import prices are very low on world
markets. There is a lot of recession out there and, therefore, prices are
very low,' he argued.
'These measures have been designed to avoid any impact on price indices. On
one hand, they will improve the prices of some exports; on the other hand,
they will produce a fall in fuel prices and transport costs,' the minister
added in his televised speech.
He said that, as of next week, the goverment will refund Argentine exporters
all taxes they pay in producing their goods, including VAT, gross income
tax, fuel and electricity duties, and taxes on assets, wages and raw
materials.
Mr Cavallo also announced new import tariffs, which were based on the degree
of value added to goods and the incidence of taxes in their production.
However, the top import tariff was cut to 20 per cent from 35 per cent, and
will be imposed on such consumer goods as clothing, home appliances and
motorcars.
The minister scrapped domestic taxes on gas oil, fuel oil and kerosene.
Mr Cavallo acknowledged in his speech that Argentina would probably finish
1992 with a trade deficit larger than Dollars 1bn, against a Dollars 3.7bn
surplus last year, but said these measures and fiscal austerity would help
the country balance its trade account more evenly in 1993.
Analysts expected the measures would offset an increasingly overvalued
currency which has crippled exports and triggered a flood of imports.
The announcement was prompted by alarm over Argentina's trade deficit, which
independent analysts put at Dollars 2bn. Industrialists blame the deficit on
Brazilian goods dumped in Argentina.
Concern is also growing over a decline in capital inflows. Central bank hard
currency purchases - a barometer of capital flows - fell to Dollars 260m
this month, the lowest rate this year and 21 per cent below that of
September.
The measures are part of a broader government attempt to recover the
political initiative, maintain growth and pave the way for Mr Menem's
controversial bid to amend the constitution so as to clear the way for
himself to stand for re-election when his term ends in 1995.
Mr Jorge Avila, an economic analyst, said the measures would amount to an
indirect devaluation. Instead of making companies more efficient, they would
encourage lobbies and corruption, but only delay an inevitable recession and
price deflation. Persistent inflation, excessive demand and a fixed exchange
rate were driving Argentina to recession, he added.
Mr Menem has also demanded an emergency package for pensioners, whose
regular weekly protests have become an embarrassment. The plight of
Argentina's 3.5m pensioners, many of whom survive on token benefits, has
become a symbol of government indifference to social problems created by its
strict free-market policies.
The docile trade unions have called a one-day general strike for November 9
to protest over low wages and government plans to attack their privileges.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
