<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Economic growth remains sluggish
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL PROWSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A MIXED bag of economic reports yesterday signalled sluggish growth for the
US economy.
Orders in September for durable goods fell for the third consecutive month,
while increases in personal incomes and consumption overstated the economy's
underlying strength, according to Commerce Department reports.
New orders for durable goods fell 0.4 per cent last month, surprising most
analysts, who had forecast a modest rebound after declines of 0.4 per cent
and 2.7 per cent in August and July respectively.
However, the weakness last month mainly reflected sharp declines in the
volatile sectors of defence and aerospace. Excluding defence, orders rose
0.5 per cent; excluding transport, they rose 2.1 per cent.
Orders for non-defence capital goods, excluding aircraft and parts - the
figure generally regarded as the best guide to trends in civilian investment
 -rose a sharp 5.5 per cent in September.
Personal income and consumption both rose 0.7 per cent - larger increases
than expected. But the income figures were distorted by a rebound after
Hurricane Andrew in August, and by subsidy payments to farmers.
Excluding distortions, personal incomes rose only 0.1 per cent last month
after a 0.6 per cent increase in August.
Official figures indicated that the apparent rebound in consumption last
month principally reflected price changes. After allowing for inflation,
personal consumption spending rose 0.1 per cent, after remaining constant in
August.
The figures were consistent with other recent data indicating the underlying
pace of economic growth is about 1.5 to 2 per cent, rather than the 2.7 per
cent reported this week by the Commerce Department.
</TEXT>
