FT  29 OCT 92 / UN elects Security Council members
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE UN Security Council, which many countries are eager to expand and
re-organise, will acquire five new members as a result of General Assembly
elections late on Tuesday.
Brazil, Pakistan, Spain, New Zealand and Djibouti will supersede Ecuador,
India, Austria, Belgium and Zimbabwe for two-year terms beginning on January
1. The changes are not expected to alter greatly voting patterns in the
15-nation council.
However, India and Zimbabwe were inclined to be fence-sitters on some
issues, including those of Iraq and former Yugoslavia, sometimes abstaining
on crucial resolutions. Pakistan and Djibouti, both Moslem countries, may be
expected to be more supportive of actions designed to help
Bosnia-Hercegovina.
Regional groups in the UN customarily offer agreed nominees for the five
elected positions that have to be filled every year. The 'western European
and others' group - the others being states of the old British Commonwealth
 -proposed three candidates to succeed Austria and Belgium, leaving the
assembly to choose two among Spain, Sweden and New Zealand.
As expected, Spain easily gained the required two-thirds majority in the
first ballot. New Zealand was a surprise winner in a third ballot,
overtaking Sweden, which had led in the first round.
Japan, Morocco, Hungary, Venezuela and the Cape Verde Islands will complete
the second year of their elected terms in 1993. The permanent members are
the US, Russia, China, Britain and France.
The question of increasing the number of permanent members will be taken up
by the assembly within the next few weeks, with Japan and Germany believing
that, as global economic powers, they deserve to join the original five.
India, Brazil, Pakistan, Egypt and Nigeria also believe they have a good
claim. The UN's 50th anniversary year, 1995, has been set informally as a
target for change.
It is not proposed that additional permanent members would have the power of
veto, last used over two years ago.
</TEXT>
