<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Prince urges lessons in education
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PRINCE of Wales yesterday said that Britain had much to learn from
France and Germany in education and training, and should do that rather than
'blame them for our problems'.
He said at a Business in the Community conference in Manchester: 'We do
ourselves no justice if we ignore that greater value is attached to
technical and vocational training, staying-on rates are higher, and better
apprenticeship arrangements prevail in some of our European partner
countries.'
He added: 'It is probably fair to say that, as a nation, we have not always
given education the priority it deserves.'
The Prince highlighted better vocational education as the main challenge.
Noting that the present resession was 'causing pain and difficulty' he
added: 'It has been particularly demoralising for those who have raised
their sights and been successful in further and higher education, only to
find that employment opportunities are still depressingly scarce.'
The Prince called for a concerted campaign to win the 'hearts and minds' of
business people, teachers, trainers, politicians and parents to the
importance of staying-on and achieving worthwhile qualifications.
He added, however, that the country needed 'the right package of support
measures: attainable but credible qualifications, appropriate courses, good
schools, and enlightened partnerships' between business, schools and the
community.
The Prince welcomed the new range of vocational qualifications coming on
stream, which are the government's answer to the problems he highlighted -
but he also stressed the importance of history, literature, art and drama to
'education for life'.
</TEXT>
