<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / El Salvador peace plan 'supported'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, EL SALVADOR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE president of El Salvador has committed his government to follow the UN
plan for bringing peace to the country, Mr Boutros Boutros Ghali, UN
secretary-general, said last night, AP reports from New York and San
Salvador.
The statement followed reports that President Alfredo Cristiani had sent a
long and confusing letter to Mr Boutros Ghali, giving qualified approval to
the UN peace plan.
The UN chief said the president had given a commitment that the government
will continue to implement its obligations under the UN agreements, subject
to continuing consultations on one unspecified point, and that it will do
nothing which could obstruct the objective of ending the armed conflict as
quickly as possible.
However, reports from El Salvador said that Mr Cristiani's letter objected
to reduction of the Salvadorean armed forces so as to purge officers
identified as death squad members or human rights abusers. plan.
Mr Cristiani is under intense pressure from extreme-right elements in his
country to reject the UN peace plan.
Salvadorean left-wing rebels announced yesterday they would demobilise on
Saturday another 1,700 fighters, as a show of support for the UN plan to
advance the peace process.
About 3,400 rebels, or 40 percent of them, would remain armed past the
weekend.
</TEXT>
