FT  29 OCT 92 / New Central Bank head
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Gustavo Loyola, a 39-year-old economist, has been nominated as the new
governor of the Brazilian Central Bank, completing the formation of the
government of Acting-President Itamar Franco, Christina Lamb reports.
Mr Loyola has spent the last 15 years in the Central Bank.
He succeeds Mr Francisco Gros, an internationally respected banker, who many
were hoping would remain. Despite lobbying for Mr Gros by the economy and
planning ministers, Mr Franco insisted that he was too closely associated
with the previous government's policy of high interest rates.
The departure of Mr Gros could signal a relaxation of monetary policy.
