<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / London Stock Exchange: Profit downgrades hurt share prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTEREST rate optimism was discouraged both in Frankfurt and London
yesterday, and the UK stock market backed away ahead of tonight's important
policy speech from Mr Norman Lamont, the British chancellor of the
exchequer.
The downward slide accelerated following a spate of profit downgradings by
securities analysts, with ICI hit hard by predictions that today's trading
statement will disclose a fall of about one quarter in earnings for the
first nine months of this year.
The renewed cutback in profit forecasts came across the range of the
industrial share sectors and reflected the perception that the recession in
the UK may plumb new depths. One of the leading UK investment banks regards
this week's heavy cutback in production by British Steel as a warning for
the markets.
Share prices opened lower and losses were quickly extended after hopes of a
rapid cut in German interest rates were dashed by the unchanged minimum
lending rates at this week's Bundesbank repurchase tender. The Bank of
England's policies in the London money markets appeared to emphasise its
message of the previous day - that no cut in UK rates was in the offing. The
implications of this check to City hopes of another early cut in domestic
interest rates was underlined by an interim trading statement from Marks and
Spencer, one of Britain's leading high street clothing and food retailers.
Although Marks' interim profits were higher, the board warned that consumer
confidence remains low and that the second half of the year will be
overshadowed by the effects on retail spending of persisting high
unemployment levels in the UK.
At least two trading programmes were identified in the market, with the
first one clearly weighted towards the sell side but the second apparently
more evenly balanced. However, once the bad news was in the market, shares
steadied in London, helped both by a much-improved performance from sterling
and also by a calm opening to the new session on Wall Street. At the close,
the FT-SE Index stood at 2,650.4 for a final loss on the day of 19.4 points.
Seaq volume of 517.2m shares, taking in at least one large share placing,
compared with 551m in the previous session when retail business was worth
Pounds 1bn, a return to the high volume levels of recent days.
The stock market is effectively on hold ahead of tonight's Mansion House
speech from the UK chancellor, in which he is expected to outline the
government's economic policies in the wake of Britain's departure from the
ERM network. But the stock market perceives that the chief test for
government strategies will not come until next week when the Maastricht
proposals will be debated in parliament.
However, few City analysts expect Mr Lamont to announce a cut in UK base
rates tonight; most believe that the next reduction in base rates will be
held back until the autumn economic statement. Yesterday's recovery in
sterling, which fell sharply at the beginning of the week, is likely to
provide a suitable stage for a reduction in UK base rates.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
