<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures and Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DERIVATIVES dealers hung fire ahead of the chancellor of the exchequer's
keynote speech tonight, writes Peter John.
One trader summed up the general view with the comment: 'Everyone knows the
market is going to move but nobody can decide which way.'
The FT-SE 100 index contract for December delivery saw interest in the
morning but activity petered out and, by the official close, only 6,653 lots
had been dealt.
December opened marginally off and was subsequently sold down to 2,680, its
low of the day. By the 4.10pm close it had rallied to 2,683, a net fall of
27 on the day. The premium above fair value (currently around 20) narrowed
to 12.
The polarisation of views on the short-term future of the economy was
reflected in the day's business. Dealers optimistic for a rate cut were
matched by those who argue that lower interest rates have been factored into
the market and, without a cut, the market will focus on political
uncertainty and fall sharply.
Business was brisker in traded options, where more than 31,000 contracts
were traded, a big increase over the past two days once extraordinary
individual trades are deducted. J. Sainsbury, a very good performer in the
underlying market and now at the top of its trading range, was the top stock
option with nearly 2,500 lots dealt.
</TEXT>
