<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Arts: Tara Arts, where East meets West - Theatre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALASTAIR MACAULAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
How very satisfying to find Tara Arts staging a co-production with the
Theatre Royal, Stratford East. Tara Arts, lest you need reminding, is the
British Asian theatre company whose versions of Tartuffe and The Little Clay
Cart has played so happily at the National Theatre and elsewhere; and the
Theatre Royal, Stratford East, has one of the liveliest, and most culturally
mixed, audiences in Britain. Part of the fun in watching Heer Ranjha, their
latest Tara production, at Stratford East is to see how well the company's
vivid performing style works here, and to hear the speed and ease with which
many of its viewers respond.
If Tara Arts is new to you, Heer Ranjha is a good primer in their style,
which commutes so fluently between Western and Asian elements that it fuses
them into one. This particular staging also commutes loveably between high
drama and low comedy, between noble utterance ('Suffer me to kiss your hand
and foot') and colloquial talk. And - never underrate this, you highbrows -
it has a good story, about how the deep love between Heer and her father's
cowherd Ranjha is threatened by her family, which successfully manages to
part the two lovers with one catastrophe after another. One of the two
musicians keeps up a lively, varied supply of music on Indian drums and
guitar.
If you have seen some previous Tara productions, you may well find Heer
Ranjha touching, entertaining, but occasionally disappointing. Let me attend
now to the disappointments. There is too much mugging and cuteness from
secondary characters; and there are moments when some of them suddenly
switch into broad London accents to make rude remarks about other characters
('What are you waiting for - bloody Christmas?'): too cheap, too
inconsistent a ploy. The music sometimes makes it hard to hear the words;
and the synthesised sound effects that one musician produces from his
electronic keyboard add a horridly unspontaneous aura to events. Some of the
Indian accents here, exaggerated for comic effect, reach the point of
impenetrability. David KS Tse, playing Ranjha, is a lightweight who works
too forcefully to compensate for his lack of heroism.
All in all, though, this show is endearing. Shelley King, with her sharp,
lined, wicked face and her sly, low voice, is an unlikely type to play the
heroine Heer; but she is a commanding figure, and becomes the embodiment of
dignity and devotion. Nirmal Chandra Pandey plays the river Chenab and other
roles with beautiful authority. Magdalen Rubalcava's designs are always
picturesque and evocative. Jatinder Verma and Christopher Shackle have
turned the original 1759 Varis Shah text into a marvellous English theatre
piece, constantly changing in mood. Verma, who is also the founder and
artistic director of Tara Arts, also directs. Thanks to his flair for true
entertainment, the Tara spell seldom falters.
At the Theatre Royal, Stratford East till November 21.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 17
</PAGE>
