<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / World Stock Markets (America): US equities firmer after late
trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US share prices firmed yesterday afternoon in spite of some bad economic
news and disappointing earnings reports, writes Patrick Harverson in New
York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average added 15.67 to close at 3,251.40, with most
of the gains coming in the last minutes of trading. The more broadly based
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was also higher, up 1.64 at 420.13, while the Amex
composite was up 2.35 at 379.00 and the Nasdaq composite 4.44 firmer at
601.39. Turnover on the NYSE was 203m shares as rises outpaced declines by
1012 to 713.
The morning's economic releases were mostly negative: while consumer
spending and personal income both rose 0.7 per cent last month, special
factors, partly related to Hurricane Andrew, distorted the figures. Some
analysts said that the overall picture was one of continued weakness.
The 0.4 per cent fall in durable goods orders in September was also worrying
as the market had been expecting a small rise.
Some of the earnings reports were equally unsettling. Ford dropped Dollars 1
3/4 to Dollars 38 1/8 in turnover of nearly 2m shares after announcing a
loss of Dollars 159m, or 43 cents a share, in the third quarter. The figures
were well below analysts' estimates of around 25 cents a share, and the
company also warned that the losses could continue into the fourth quarter.
Borden fell Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 27 after announcing a net loss for the
quarter of Dollars 376.8m, a marked deterioration from the Dollars 98m
profit earned a year earlier. The loss was incurred, however, after the
company took a Dollars 450m restructuring charge that will help pay for the
closure of some packaging plants in Europe and the withdrawal from some
North American snacks operations.
Better news was forthcoming from USF&amp;G, which rose Dollars  1/2 to Dollars
12 1/4 after the insurance group unveiled consolidated net income of Dollars
5m in the third quarter, an improvement on the Dollars 25m loss at the same
stage in 1991. The company also reported a continued improvement in its core
property/casualty operations.
Tandem Computers climbed Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 13 5/8 in after Morgan
Stanley, the securities house, responded to the recent good earnings figures
by raising its profit forecast for Tandem's current fiscal year and
upgrading its rating on the stock.
Life Re enjoyed a strong debut. More than 10m shares of the reinsurer were
floated at Dollars 22 each, and reached Dollars 24 7/8 at the end of the
day.
Airlines remained strong, in spite of further competitive price-cutting.
AMR, parent of American, rose Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 64 1/4 and UAL held
steady at Dollars 121 3/8 although Delta slid Dollars 1/2 to Dollars 58 3/8
, reversing its morning gains.
Canada
TORONTO stocks rallied to end sharply higher as uncertainty surrounding
Canada's constitution fades and investors focus on the economy and potential
declines in interest rates.
Volume on the TSE index swelled to its highest level since December 15,
1988, ending up 48.3 points at 3,334.7 on turnover of 48.3m valued at
CDollars 495.5m.
Advancing issues led those declining 370 to 194 while 262 remained
unchanged.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
