<DOCNO>FT924-10741</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJ2B8AEMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Observer: Right track
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Nelson Mandela, the African National Congress leader, will have made no
friends for himself in South Africa's townships with his announcement this
week that he wants to appoint Lee Kuan Yew as an economic adviser to the
ANC. Singapore's former prime minister, now on a visit to the country, would
find few kindred spirits among the ANC's other economic advisers, many of
whom are Marxists - not to mention in the townships where the 'workers'
still expect to inherit the earth with the help of the ANC.
The choice reveals Mandela at his pragmatic best. He says openly that the
state of the South African economy, in its fourth year of recession,
frightens him silly. If it takes Lee Kuan Yew to get growth back on track,
so be it.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
