<DOCNO>FT924-10742</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJ2B8AELFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Observer: Bleeding hearts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
When a letter pleading for funds dropped on the mat last week from Housing
and Urban Development Secretary Jack Kemp, many US Republicans assumed that
the self-styled 'bleeding heart conservative' was cutting loose from the
sinking Bush ship to launch his own bid for 1996.
But the missive turns out to be a carefully disguised gesture of loyalty
towards a president who has repeatedly spurned Kemp's efforts to push a more
aggressive domestic policy. What it does show is the depth of the
Republicans' money troubles - which are further blighting a seemingly
hopeless campaign.
The Republican finance committee has apparently given up using Bush's name
to haul in the loot. While Kemp's letter repeatedly warns how disastrous it
would be for the Democrats to win, it mentions Bush just once, and then in
the past tense.
In the past two months, the normally flush Republicans have seen funds
dwindle to a trickle; donors have started to hedge their bets by giving to
the Clinton cause.
Although the Republicans have raised Dollars 10m more than the Democrats
since the beginning of 1991, they are now running so far short of previous
totals that campaign managers are still having to schedule fund-raising
appearances for Dan Quayle, who ought to be beating the bushes for votes,
not money.
Of course, if Bush loses, no-one could blame Kemp. . .
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-10743</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJ2B8AEKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Economic Viewpoint: Time for helicopters and holes in the
ground
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SAMUEL BRITTAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is something futile about a depression. Real economic problems arise
from rival and clamorous claims on scarce resources. Other problems arise
from reducing the inflation rate, which can have a heavy transitional cost.
But depression - defined as too little spending to secure trend economic
growth even when inflation is low - seems a paradoxical sort of evil.
To put down a few numbers. A reasonable growth rate for the UK national
income in money terms (nominal gross domestic product), consistent with low
inflation and a very gradual emergence from recession, might be 5 per cent
per annum or just above. The present underlying growth rate of the money
national income is probably about 2 or 3 per cent per annum or less. This
means that even with core inflation down to about 3 or 4 per cent, output
continues to fall, adding to recessionary pressures in an already depressed
economy.
Worst of all the depression is contributing to a mood of acute xenophobia
combined with hostility to market solutions which I can only call
national(istic) socialism and is particularly vociferous among some of the
so-called Tory Euro-sceptics.
I doubt the widespread view that the depression is due to political fears.
The severity of the first dip was often attributed to the Gulf war in 1991.
When the end of the war failed to set off a recovery, the second dip was
attributed to election fears. Now the third dip is being attributed to the
trials of a weak government. These are late rationalisations.
Yet for all the gloom there are few people who cannot think of ways of
spending more money so long as they have enough of it. Milton Friedman has
spoken of a helicopter dropping dollar bills. Keynes wrote about burying
pound notes in holes in the ground.
What are the objections to some dressed-up version of the helicopter or the
hole?
A serious objection is that governments could overestimate the amount of
unused capacity or unemployed labour that could be brought back into use by
injecting more demand. In that case too much of the stimulus would take the
form of more inflation rather than genuine growth. In addition the consumer
response could be unmanageably jerky: to begin with very little, and then a
sudden and unexpected upward jerk in spending which would be difficult to
pull back. Above all, there is the danger of generating a fall in sterling
which would increase the inflationary component of any given stimulus.
Demand management is and will remain an imperfect art, but allowing a
cumulative downward cycle to develop is itself dangerous. The domestic risks
can be reduced if demand management is moved a step away from the political
process, so that - for instance - base rate changes cannot be timed to help
the government out of a parliamentary difficulty. Just as important is
commitment to a nominal objective which puts a limit to the inflationary
potential if things go wrong. The little word 'nominal' is not just a
gesture to monetarists, but the heart of the exercise.
The inflationary impact of sterling's recent depreciation could be spread
over a longer period than that of previous devaluations and therefore have a
smaller impact on the per annum inflation rate.
Keith Skeoch of James Capel has shown that sterling is historically
extremely competitive against the D-Mark and once again quite competitive
against the dollar, following the latter's recovery. The CBI October survey
also records the sharpest turnround from pessimism to optimism about export
prospects since 1987, even though the world slowdown will delay the impact.
The shock horror effect from the CBI survey comes from domestic questions,
above all from the highly psychological one which does reflect the political
factor but which is also extremely volatile. However, as I tried to show in
an article in the FT on October 12 (Sense on Sterling) these gains will turn
into inflationary dross if the pound continues to sink. We are already in
the danger area and should be looking for some recovery.
The moral is that any further stimulus should take a fiscal form rather than
the cuts in base rates about which John Major talks so much to the lobby.
The common-sense reason for not cutting, and even adding to, public capital
projects, is that it is best to undertake them when the construction
industry is slack and it is easier to get value for money. And when
confidence is important, why not put these projects below some line on a
piece of paper so that accountants can say that they form a 'capital
budget'?
But there are no grounds for cutting social security payments, which feed
straight through into consumer spending, other than to prevent abuses which
should be tackled irrespective of the economic temperature. Nor are there
any grounds for laying off public sector workers other than genuine
over-manning. And it would be hair shirt stupidity to raise taxes. But a
tight public sector pay limit makes a lot of sense.
The objection that a looser fiscal policy would drive up interest rates is
badly flawed. As the chart shows, a soaring public sector borrowing
requirement has in the past couple of years been accompanied by tumbling
interest rates at both the short and the long end. Even in earlier years
there is little systematic relationship between budget deficits and interest
rates.
The error that is made is to treat the UK as a closed economy in which the
government can borrow more only by 'printing money' or by bidding up
interest rates. In a free world capital market there is a going rate for
funds; and borrowing governments pay an interest penalty if their currencies
are expected to depreciate or if they are judged to be default risks. A
little bit of 'printing money' in the shape of underfunding the budget
deficit could well be tried - the equivalent to a few rotations of the
helicopter's blades.
In the end it may be cost-effective to take a more unorthodox approach. If
central bankers, led by Paul Volcker, the former chairman of the US Fed,
could 10 years ago assemble first aid packages for developing countries,
there seems no reason why governments and central banks should not
domestically offer to take over from building societies and banks a slice of
the debt of households with negative equity - or alternatively to make some
direct contribution to interest costs. These operations would - like the US
savings and loan rescues - be put in a category of their own outside the
normal budget, which would then really have to balance once economic
activity got back to trend.
Taking risks with sterling and interest rates, while making gestures to
fiscal orthodoxy, seems to be the prevailing policy mix. It is the opposite
of what is required; but it is what we shall get.
</TEXT>
