<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Letter: Concern over US transfer pricing proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr T A SYMONS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Earlier this year the US Treasury and Internal Revenue Service issued
new draft transfer pricing regulations. These could have far reaching - and
dramatic - implications for foreign multinationals in the US. Price
Waterhouse has closely consulted representatives of British industry and
made detailed representations to the US tax authorities to urge that the
worst excesses of the proposed rules are avoided.
As drafted, the regulations overturn the internationally accepted
arm's-length standard for transfer pricing. Instead, they elevate one method
frequently used by tax authorities as a way of checking the reasonableness
of transfer prices (ie comparing a company's results with those of its
competitors) to virtually the sole determinant of prices, with little
flexibility for adjusting results for differences in economic circumstances.
The draft regulations also seem to require companies to recalculate royalty
rates charged for the use of patents or trademarks every few years.
If these new rules are adopted, conflict between taxpayers and tax
authorities - and between tax authorities - is expected to increase. The use
of the recently introduced Advance Pricing Agreement procedure is likely to
be of limited assistance in overcoming this problem.
Fortunately, in response to detailed criticisms the IRS at last appears to
be modifying its original approach. It has recently indicated that the
comparison of results pricing method may have a lower priority than
originally planned and there may also be more flexibility in relation to
intangibles and in other areas.
However, because of the high profile of the issue in the US, there must be
concern that the rules could change again. It is to be hoped that Britain's
tax authorities continue to make strenuous representations so that
potentially serious damage is averted.
Terry Symons,
Price Waterhouse,
Southwark Towers,
London SE1 9SY
</TEXT>
