<TEXT>
Sir, You quote Ms Colette Flesch, the head of the information directorate,
as wishing to bring about an emotional link with the Community and the
positive things it has brought about ('Brussels tries to plug an information
gap', October 26).
This demonstrates where the Commission's information programme is going
wrong. It is unequivocal facts about the Commission's aspirations and
activities that should be communicated, not emotions of the Berlaymont
residents.
Earlier this year, I had the unrewarding experience of acting as media
relations adviser to President Delors' cabinet office in promoting their
association with the Winter Olympics. The officials' preoccupations turned
out to be:
a) avoiding firm statements about the Ecu10m being invested in this
'corporate sponsorship' of winter and summer Olympics;
b) ensuring that all material was issued in either three or nine languages,
approval for which had to be sanctioned by a Brussels Committee.
The result was that 'news' issued was bland and out of date by the time it
was approved for release. If President Delors is serious about closing the
information gap, he should ensure that the decision chain for releasing
material is short, effective and responsive to the external market.
Christopher J Bailey,
partner,
