<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Letter: More a criticism of British management than of
quality
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Dr DAVID LAWSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, The Economist Intelligence Unit report, Lessons from Europe's Leading
Companies, and Paul Taylor's article, 'Why customers must come first'
(Management, October 26), are much more a criticism of British management
than of quality management.
They implicitly reveal the reason for much of the failure of British
management; its almost insatiable desire for the miracle cure, the latest
fad and the quick fix. These 'star dust' or 'flavour of the month'
approaches are introduced into the organisation by a senior manager in the
hope that it will instantly cure all his problems, while he continues 'to
get on with running the business' in exactly the same way that he always
did. When, not surprisingly, the cure is treated with cynicism by the
employees and does not deliver, the manager merely goes on to the next
panacea.
Total quality management (TQM) has fallen into this 'instant cure' category
in the minds of many managers. Their damaging misconception has been
pandered to and reinforced by many so-called management consultants who
peddle easy, quick and glossy packages called 'TQM' which are claimed to
achieve remarkable results almost without effort. As the report points out,
they don't work.
Total quality management is not quick nor is it effortless. The concepts are
easy to understand and to explain but it takes continuous and personal
commitment by managers to implement them. TQM is the effective and efficient
way of running an organisation to satisfy all its customers and shareholders
continuously, on the basis of continuous improvement. Successful
implementation of such a continuous improvement process is not only
possible, it is the prerequisite of being viable in the international
market. It is a very sad reflection on British management that this
minimalist requirement does, in fact, offer a major competitive edge in our
home market.
David Lawson,
Crosby Associates UK,
Centenary House,
5 Hill Street,
Richmond, Surrey TW9 1SP
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 19
