<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Observer: Short-changed
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Well, it's one way to add names to the shareholder register.
When Hendon fruiterer Harold Isaaman recently went into the Midland branch
opposite his shop to change a tenner into one pound coins, the cashier
offered him just eight pounds. She explained that she was deducting a fee of
two pounds for this simple little service.
'Oh, Mr Isaaman,' sighed a bank spokesman, when Observer rang to discuss the
policy on small change. 'He's not even a customer of the bank.' Midland then
explained that, if you don't bank there, you can expect a charge of 2 per
cent, with a Pounds 2 minimum - levied at the discretion of the local
manager.
Nor is it just the listening bank. Lloyds says that for non-customers
changing money on a regular basis it will expect to collect Pounds 3 per
transaction. Barclays goes one better and explains: 'We'd rather they (non
customers) didn't come to us at all. We might suggest they go somewhere
else.'
So an incensed Isaaman went out this week and bought two shares in Midland's
new owners, the Hongkong &amp; Shanghai Banking Corporation. Now he can turn up
at the next agm to see if his fellow shareholders think this is the way for
recession-bound institutions to create goodwill and expand their customer
base.
</TEXT>
