<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: Low prices force 16-day closure
of zinc-lead mine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING, Mining Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER zinc fell to its lowest price for 9 1/2 months in London yesterday,
Curragh Resources said low prices were forcing it to close the Faro
zinc-lead complex in the Yukon for 16 days over the Christmas period.
The Canadian mining group said this would cut output by about 25,000 tonnes,
two-thirds of which is zinc, and affect about 300 staff. It said it was
setting budgets for 1993 and Faro, with an annual output of about 500,000
tonnes of metal, might have to shut down some capacity next year.
Analysts suggested Curragh's action was unlikely to raise zinc prices. 'This
won't turn the market,' said Mr Nick Moore, analyst at Ord Minnett, part of
the Westpac banking group. 'Zinc will need a much bigger shock than this.
Production cutbacks so far have been pretty tentative but this price of
about 50 cents a lb will force producers to make more cuts.'
However, he said the market should note that labour contract negotiations
were in progress at three big zinc smelters - Cominco's Trail and Sullivan
smelters (245,000 and 190,000 tonnes a year respectively) and Noranda's
Valleyfield (220,000 tonnes). 'But the ball is not exactly in the union's
court at the moment.'
Mr Angus MacMillan, research manager at Billiton-Enthoven Metals, part of
the Royal Dutch/Shell group, pointed out that the zinc market was likely to
experience another supply surplus this year - of about 150,000 tonnes
following one of 85,000 tonnes in 1991.
On the London Metal Exchange yesterday, zinc for delivery in three months
touched Dollars 1,110 a tonne at one point.
This sparked some consumer interest and the price recovered to close at
Dollars 1,118.50 a tonne, down Dollars 14 from Tuesday's close.
London Metal Exchange stock figures were misleading because not all the
metal was immediately available, Mr Martin Abbott, the LME's marketing
director pointed out yesterday.
Unlike producers' stocks, those in LME warehouses had been bought by someone
for some good reason and the owner might not be a ready seller. He said
metals producers and consumers were carrying minimal stocks so any recovery
in industrial activity was likely to see LME stocks evaporating quickly.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 30
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-10754</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJ2B8AD9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: A silk purse for the pig
breeders - The creation of a Chinese-European super-sow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BLACKWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MEISHAN pig from the Lake Taihu region of north-west China looks as if
it belongs in a zoo. It has a hide reminiscent of a rhinoceros, a face like
a basset-hound with a snout, and eyes that disappear behind ridges of fat.
Pig breeders, however, have long admired Meishans for their astonishingly
high reproduction rate. A Meishan sow has up to 20 teats, compared with 12
to 14 in a British breed, and regularly delivers 16 piglets. She can also
come into puberty in as little as 2 1/2 to 3 months compared with 6 months
for a European pig. But when fully grown the Chinese pig is all fat and
bone, with little lean meat - hence the Chinese passion for suckling pigs.
Now one of the leading UK pig breeding companies has succeeded in capturing
the prolificity of the Meishan in a pig with lean meat. Far from being in a
zoo, the Meishan is at the centre of a high-tech breeding programme aimed at
transforming the productivity and profitability of the pig industry.
The National Pig Development Company of Driffield, East Yorkshire, was one
of five breeding companies that formed a consortium to import the first
Meishans into the UK in 1987. Until then political problems had prevented
the Chinese from exporting.
The first animals went to the Institute of Animal Physiology and Genetic
Research in Edinburgh for research into the genes carrying prolificity. When
the numbers were sufficient, animals were released to the five breeders.
Mr Stephen Curtis, managing director for production at NPD, believes that
his company was the first to breed a commercial hybrid because of its drive
over the last 20 years to produce pigs with a high lean meat content. He
proudly points out that for eight years the company has come out top in
tests conducted by the Meat and Livestock Commission. 'Because we are that
much leaner, by systematically crossing our pigs with the Chinese pig we've
been able to produce a hybrid with an acceptable carcass that is only
slightly fatter than a standard hybrid,' he says.
NPD was founded in 1969 by Mr John Curtis, who was anxious for his two sons
to be able to earn their living from farming. He decided to concentrate on
pigs as he felt poultry were being overproduced and cattle and sheep were
too long-term.
He remains chairman of the company, which now has an annual turnover of
about Pounds 20m, some 250 employees and what he believes are the best
computerised records in the industry. 'The pig development industry is only
25 years old - by many standards this is rather new,' says his other son
David, who runs the marketing division. 'We are becoming more and more
sophisticated.' The pigmen at NPD need to know as much about computers as
they do about buckets of swill.
Each pig at the company's 24 farms and the thousands of farms it supplies
with breeding stock is tattooed with an individual number and has its own
computer record.
The computer programme stores a complete medical record for 150,000 breeding
sows, and knows exactly how productive each animal is. Stephen Curtis
believes use of the computer has increased the accuracy of breeding
selection by 15 per cent and put the company three to four years ahead of
the opposition.
The new hybrid, known as the Manor Meishan, was launched in some style at
the Cafe Royal in London last May. Next year the company plans to sell 6,000
breeding gilts, worth Pounds 225 each, in the UK. But David Curtis also has
ambitious plans for the US market.
Last year it signed a franchise agreement with Smithfield-Carroll, a large
pork company based in Virginia, which is taking NPD's breeding stock. Every
six weeks a jumbo jet carrying 800 pigs flies to the US to build up a
breeding stock that is expected to reach 1m sows by the year 2000.
However, the Manor Meishan will not be sent to the US until the UK market is
satisfied. 'We have always taken the view that you need to be strong at home
to give a springboard for work abroad,' says John Curtis. At present NPD
claims 20 per cent of the UK gilts market.
Eventually some Manor Meishans could even find their way back to their
ancestral homeland. Scientists from China's Guizhou Province this summer
visited NPD as part of a programme to improve production of pork, which
makes up 90 per cent of the meat consumed in the province.
</TEXT>
