<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: First private sector copper
smelter to be built in India
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RC MURTHY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BOMBAY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INDIA'S FIRST private-sector copper smelter is to be built near Bombay in
collaboration with MIM Holdings of Australia.
Copper smelting, reserved for the public sector, was deregulated last year
as part of an overall industrial liberalisation policy. Now Sterlite
Industries, producer of copper rods, has announced that it is setting up a
smelter to produce 60,000 tonnes of copper cathodes a year from imported
concentrates, probably from Zambia or Chile.
India has a 47,500-tonne smelter, which is operating at half of its
capacity, and most of the local requirements are met by imports.
Few copper smelters have been built in industrial countries in recent years,
partly because of the introduction of new methods of producing copper and
partly because of strict environmental laws.
Thailand and Indonesia, which also have planned copper smelters, are talking
to MIM about buying the technology.
Every year as by-products, the Sterlite copper smelter will produce seven
tonnes of gold, which will be higher than India's present total gold
production of five tonnes, and some 20 tonnes of silver.
Mr Anil Agarwal, chairman, says annual demand for copper in India is
expected to rise from the present 150,000 tonnes to 250,000 tonnes in 1995.
He claims the smelter will be competitive internationally because it will
use latest technology.
</TEXT>
