<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Money Markets: German policy tight
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RATES in the sterling cash market continued to ease yesterday as dealers
waited to see whether the chancellor will signal a cut in base rates to
coincide with tonight's Mansion House speech, writes James Blitz.
However, Euromark futures were pushed lower as hopes vanished of an official
rate cut at today's Bundesbank meeting. The Bundesbank dashed hopes of an
easing by allocating 'repo' funds to the cash market at a minimum interest
rate of 8.75 per cent, a level that was unchanged from last week.
Sterling markets continue to be the most bullish in Europe. Many people
assume that another base rate cut is in the offing. That expectation was
reflected in dealers' unwillingness to offer bills to the Bank of England
yesterday. The Bank forecast a shortage of Pounds 800m at the start of
yesterday's operations, but, in the morning, the authorities only bought
Pounds 124m in a repurchase agreement at the established rate of 7 15/16 per
cent. Dealers had probably offered to sell bills at lower rates, but were
turned down.
Later, the market relaxed, and Pounds 715m of liquidity was added in the
afternoon after the Bank increased the shortage to Pounds 850m. One-month
money, at which a lot of banks do their market borrowing, closed at around 8
3/8 per cent from a previous close of 8 per cent. The 3-month rate dropped
from around 7 13/16 per cent to 7 1/2 per cent, the lowest it has been since
the last base rate cut.
Some dealers were expecting conditions to be much tighter today. There may
be heavier speculation on a rate cut, and assets will not be sold easily.
The Bundesbank signalled in its money market operations that there will be
no official rate change after it refrained from engineering a reduction in
short-term rates in the weekly round of securities repurchase agreements.
Mr Hermann Rempsberger, chief economist at BHF bank in Frankfurt, was quoted
as saying that he would be very surprised if there was a change in official
policy today. 'The repo rates will have to move first,' he said. The
December Euromark contract closed down 7 basis points from its opening level
at 91.73, suggesting that 3-month money will be at 8.27 per cent by
Christmas. December French franc futures closed unchanged at 90.91.
</TEXT>
