<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Survey of Hungary (11): A spanner in the works / Profile of
Istvan Csurka
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HUNGARY now has its own hobgoblin. His name is Istvan Csurka and he believes
in things such as the 'Paris, New York, Tel Aviv' conspiracy. His goal is to
defend what he sees as true Magyars from the machinations of international
bankers, former communists, liberals and Jews.
Mr Csurka, a slow-moving, portly writer, with a mane of grey hair swept
straight up from his forehead, is one of six vice-presidents of the
Hungarian Democratic Forum, the leading member of Hungary's three party
coalition government.
On August 20, he threw a fire-cracker into the outwardly placid Hungarian
political pond with the publication of his political manifesto.
It was a rambling tract of 18,000 words, the political musings of what
fellow-writers see as a talented but essentially irresponsible man steeped
in Hungarian lore and traditions but ignorant of foreign languages and
places.
A solitary figure, fond of horse racing and gambling, Mr Csurka appeals to
racial bigots, those who fear for the survival of this small nation with its
distinctive language and those alienated by the dramatic social and economic
changes unleashed by the opening up of the economy to large scale foreign
investment.
Having inherited right wing, nationalist views from his father, a journalist
close to the wartime Arrow Cross fascist movement, Mr Csurka was subjected
to periods of enforced silence by the former communist regime. However,
under the same regime he also received several prestigious literary prizes.
His plays and novels have received critical and popular acclaim while his
weekly radio programme, broadcast every Sunday, is widely listened to. For
good or ill, Mr Csurka is a force to be reckoned with in Hungarian affairs.
His decision to stir up Hungary's political waters was ostensibly motivated
by the ill health of Mr Jozsef Antall, the prime minister, and the need to
designate an eventual successor and redefine the role and policies of the
HDF. In so doing he has staked out his position as the ideologue of the
right wing nationalist faction of the HDF.
Mr Csurka sees plots and enemies on all sides and he vehemently attacked Mr
Arpad Goencz, the Hungarian president (and fellow writer) for his refusal to
sign a government decree sacking the heads of Hungarian state radio and TV.
But what set alarm bells ringing was his attacks on gypsies, Jews, bankers,
communists and foreigners and his proposal to enlist 'healthy' young
Hungarians in the recovery of a wider Lebensraum for the the Christian
Magyar people.
Ironically this xenophobic populism, with fascist undertones, makes him
closer to former communists such as Vladimir Meciar in Slovakia, Ion
Iliescu, the newly re-elected president of Romania or Slobodan Milosevic of
Serbia than to the free market-orientated democrats of his own party or the
liberal Hungarian opposition.
The communist-nationalist leaders in surrounding states are making Hungarian
and other minorities scapegoats for economic and political difficulties in
areas which once were once totally or partially included in the greater
Hungary that disappeared with the 1920 Trianon treaty. Against this
background, Mr Csurka looks like the classic man in a glasshouse throwing
stones.
With Serbia threatening to destabilise the ethnic Hungarian areas of
Vojvodina by resettling Serb refugees from Croatia and Bosnia, and ethnic
Hungarians in Slovakia worried about their fate under Mr Meciar, Mr Csurka's
brand of national intolerance and support for Hungarian irredentism risks
leading to a dangerous escalation of provocations and abuse throughout the
region.
That might confirm Mr Csurka as a prophet in his own country. But such an
outcome would inevitably draw Hungary ever deeper into the intrigue and
instability for which Balkan politics has long been famous.
It would be incompatible with the image of contemporary Hungary, a country
striving for democracy with prosperity, and full integration into the
European Community and the wider world.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 34
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-10765</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJ2B8ADXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Survey of Hungary (9): A fragile peace - Foreign policy
makers see stability in the EC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE post-Maastricht disarray in western Europe is viewed with a mixture of
foreboding and disbelief in Hungary, where full membership of a strong
European Community is the one policy goal which is shared by all political
parties.
With over 3.5m ethnic Hungarians living in neighbouring states since the
1920 Trianon Treaty cut the country to one third of its former size, Hungary
looks towards the Community not only as inspiration for its own social and
economic progress but also as the ultimate protector of the rights of
minorities in this part of Europe.
Confidence in the EC's ability to effectively defend these rights has been
dented by events in Yugoslavia. For the Community to help preserve the
fragile new democracies, Hungarian foreign policy makers believe it needs
both a strong Commission and an extensive body of binding EC law.
It also needs the political will to demand compliance with Community
standards on human rights as the pre-condition for trade, aid and other
concessions.
The idea that widening the community to include the newly sovereign east and
central European states would weaken efforts to 'deepen' the community and
its institutions finds little echo in Budapest. 'We have no desire to dilute
the powers of the European Commission.
'We think that the stronger and more united the EC is, the easier it will be
to join,' said a senior official of the ruling Hungarian Democratic Forum.
Neither does Hungary share the concern about long-term prospects of a new
German hegemony in Europe felt by other countries in the region which were
occupied during the war.
Having worked closely with Austria during the last decades of the
Austro-Hungarian Empire and as an ally of Nazi Germany in the last war,
Hungarians have fewer hang-ups about Germany than the former 'subject
nations' of the Hapsburg Empire who suffered most from Nazi occupation 50
years ago.
At the same time, however, Budapest is acutely aware of the historical
resentments against Hungarians in surrounding states such as Slovakia and in
Transylvania where Hungarians were the rulers and are now the ruled.
Ugly scenes at a recent football match in Bratislava when Slovak riot
police, faces hidden by Balaclava helmets, were let loose against Hungarian
supporters showed how easily passions can be aroused.
After years of increasingly fraught discussions over the fate of the
Gabcikovo dam, originally conceived as a joint, communist-era
Hungarian-Czechoslovak power project on the Danube, the EC finally stepped
in earlier this month by inviting both Hungarian and Slovak delegates to
Brussels in a last minute search for a compromise.
Until now the Hungarian government has refused to be provoked and tried to
settle problems - including the future of the Gabcikovo dam and those
connected with refugees from the fighting in Croatia and over-flights by
Yugoslav aircraft - through diplomatic channels.
But this has opened up the government to charges of weakness by Hungarian
nationalists who complain, for example, at the government's inability to
restrain Mr Gheorghe Funar, the Romanian nationalist mayor of the
Transylvanian city of Cluj from banning Hungarian street names, a gratuitous
insult to its large ethnic Hungarian minority.
With fragile coalition governments in power throughout the region, the
temptation to revive latent ethnic animosities as a diversion from the
problems of implementing meaningful reforms is high and probably rising.
Much depends on the strength of the Hungarian government's will to prevent
incidents escalating into full scale international crises.
Hungarian traders meanwhile are in the forefront of attempts to forge a new
economic and political relationship with the former Soviet republics.
With over 80,000 Ikarus buses throughout the former Soviet Union needing
spare parts and oil and gas enterprises short of pipes and machinery,
Hungarian traders have created new direct trade and barter links with energy
producing areas such as Tatarstan and Bashkiria.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
