<DOCNO>FT924-10766</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJ2B8ADWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Survey of Hungary (10): Who's who in Hungary
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Tamas Szabo, privatisation minister: in Mr Szabo, western investment bankers
have the 'heavy hitter' that some think the great sell-off needs. Aware that
public support is crucial to success, he has brought a political touch to
privatisation. Mr Szabo is of that rare breed of Hungarian politician who
tries to clear a day a week to visit his constituency.
Andras Simor, head of CA Securities, the Hungarian brokerage and investment
banking subsidiary of Creditanstalt, the Austrian bank: Mr Simor has helped
carve out for CA a large share of the small to medium-sized deals which the
larger international advisers disdain but which have proved easiest
conclude. Sandor Rudnay, partner at Price Waterhouse in Budapest: one of the
most respected auditors in the business. Several of his clients decided to
follow him from KPMG to PW when he defected recently.
Rudnay is a name which crops up frequently in Hungarian business life.
Sandor's brother Janos, who also left Hungary with the family in 1956 and
has now returned, is one of the most influential western executives, heading
Philips's Hungarian operations and the new multinational lobbying
association.
Andras Kereszty, editor-in-chief of Nepszabadsag: Mr Kereszty has managed
the formidable task of taking the much-hated former communist party
newspaper and turning it into Hungary's most respected daily. The masthead
remains the same - the name means 'people-freedom' - but the coverage has
become increasingly objective.
Gabor Varszegi, entrepreneur: Mr Varszegi has built up the Fotex retailing
group into Hungary's largest homegrown private company. In the process he
has acquired a reputation for shrewdness and ruthlessness. He was a rock
star until the early 1980s and then spent a few years in the diamond trade
in New York. George Lang, restauranteur: Mr Lang is the man who has brought
power-lunching to Budapest.
Creator of the Four Seasons and Cafe des Artistes in New York, he has
brought his skills and money back to his birthplace of Hungary to revamp the
country's most famous restaurant, the Gundel.
George Lang and his partner, Ronald Lauder of the cosmetics dynasty, paid
Dollars 8m and invested at least that much again in the Gundel to bring it
back to its pre-war standards. That is more than most Hungarian industrial
plants are worth.
Les Nemethy, deputy managing director in charge of transactions of the State
Property Agency, the privatisation authority: 'Made in Hungary, born in
Canada,' Mr Nemethy likes to say of himself. His parents left during the
1956 revolution and he was born soon afterwards. After a career in mergers
and acquisitions in Canada, he is now back to the place of his conception.
Mr Nemethy has already brought some western efficiency to the SPA and
investment bankers almost universally welcome his presence. 'He speaks the
same language,' says one.
Lajos Bokros, managing director of Budapest Bank: Mr Bokros has proved
surprisingly effective as managing director, pursuing a tough write-off
policy, bringing in new management and preparing the large state bank for
privatisation.
Mr Bokros, an economist by training, rose to head the National Bank of
Hungary's capital markets department. But, in the great Hungarian tradition
of second jobs, he also freelanced as president of the Budapest Stock
Exchange (which he remains), a member of the State Property Agency board as
well as an occasional lecturer.
Miklos Nemeth, vice-president of the European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development: No one in eastern Europe can have had a better transition than
Mr Nemeth, Hungary's last communist prime minister.
After a decent interval, Mr Nemeth, whose government attracts more nostalgia
as the economic recession drags on, could quite plausibly re-enter Hungarian
politics. Peter Magyar, partner at Baker &amp; McKenzie, the longest-established
western law firm, crops up in so many deals that people joke that he is the
only lawyer in Budapest. George Soros, Hungarian-American fund manager, has
given approaching Dollars 100m out of his immense personal fortune to
eastern Europe and large bit of that to Hungary through the Soros
Foundation.
Not all Hungarians are grateful, however. Government MPs have mounted
increasingly vitriolic attacks on Mr Soros, who is Jewish and is perceived
to support opposition liberals. Gyorgy Rasko, state secretary at the
agriculture ministry: is a rare example of a professional civil servant. His
responsibilities for Hungary's agricultural sector also give him a big say
in privatisation, which has been especially concentrated in the food
industry.
Mr Rasko, a refreshingly frank man, admits that he is in a difficult
position, buffetted on the one side by foreign investors with strong
bargaining positions and on the other by government MPs who are increasingly
demanding domestic participation in privatisation.
George Varga, chief executive at GE-Tungsram, General Electric's Hungarian
subsidiary. Mr Varga, doyen of the western multinationals who took over in
1990 as chief executive, has radically restructured the company and lobbied
fruitlessly against the Hungarian government's strong currency policy.
Gyorgy Jaksity, director of Lupis Brokerhaz, one of Hungary's largest
independent broker. The 25-year-old Mr Jaksity does not think his age
matters to clients.
'Financial analysis in Hungary dates back to 1990; no one has any more
experience than two years,' he says.
Mr Jaksity is also a novelist. His first published work about Socrates
reborn in eastern Europe was a failure, however. For the time being he is
sticking to the financial world, where he is rather more successful.
Marc Holtzman, a director of EurAmerica Capital Corporation, an investment
bank supported by the Hungarian-American Enterprise Fund: Mr Holtzman has
proved that networking recognises no boundaries.
When he organised a Budapest charity dinner for Romanian orphans he brought
out the whole post-communist establishment: multinational executives, local
entrepreneurs politicians from the president down, cardinals and
ambassadors.
</TEXT>
