<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Book Review: The wonder years
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MALCOLM RUTHERFORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HAROLD WILSON By Ben Pimlott HarperCollins, Pounds 20, 811 pages
Harold Wilson has been lucky in the timing of this book, the nearest to an
official biography published so far. His stock, as a prime minister due for
revaluation, has been rising steadily in recent months. Ben Pimlott, the
author, has been fortunate, too. Some of the similarities between parts of
the Wilson period and the turmoils that John Major has been going through in
the past few weeks are uncanny. Since the parallels may be temporary, and
therefore superficial, the best thing to do is to read the book now while it
is still hot.
Red hot, or as Wilson himself might have put it, white hot. There are two
factors which marred the Wilson administrations which are with us still. One
was the weakness of the British economy, which had a corresponding effect on
the exchange rate. The other was Europe: in or out or somewhere in between?
For the historian, the question is whether Wilson did a reasonable job in
the circumstances, or whether he could have done better. The case for the
former has risen, as successive prime ministers have failed to come to terms
with Europe and the economy.
Wilson had a long experience of devaluation. As the youngest member of the
cabinet since 1806, he lived through the agonies that led to the devaluation
of 1949. Although it may have been necessary, it brought no immediate
solution to the country's economic problems. For Wilson, Pimlott notes, it
was an experience never to be repeated.
That comment says a lot about Wilson's approach when he became prime
minister in 1964. Hindsight has it that all might have been better if the
new Labour government had devalued straightaway. In fact, the formal
devaluation was staved off until late 1967, and even then it did not end the
succession of sterling crises and the need to curb public expenditure. Some
people who claim to have said that the case for a quick change in the
exchange rate was obvious did not say so at the time. In all that, we may
catch a foretaste of the present government grappling with sterling and the
ERM this autumn.
On Europe Wilson was initially an agnostic. Subsequently, when prime
minister, he was a convert. When reverting to leader of the opposition, he
was a waverer. Finally, when prime minister again, he became a believer in
putting the choice to the people. He picked up the idea of a popular vote
from Tony Benn, and for a while the referendum in 1975 seemed to have
settled the issue once and for all. Wilson was criticised for those
tergiversations, but at least he could claim that he held the party, and to
some extent the country, together.
In this respect, Pimlott is perceptive. He notes that the more Wilson seemed
committed to Europe, the more sterling seemed suspect on the foreign
exchange markets. The markets did not believe that Britain was ready to
accept all the disciplines of even the early Community.
There are, of course, differences between Wilson and his successors as prime
minister. Only Wilson had to deal with the tantrums of George Brown, who, as
deputy leader of the party, was a brilliant and popular man in his way, but
erratic and desperately worried about losing his seat in the 1970 general
election.
Far more important was Vietnam. The Americans wanted British support for the
war, which - to put it mildly - the Labour movement was reluctant to give.
On the other hand, Britain wanted American help to prop up sterling. It was
an uneasy compromise. Wilson fudged his way through, but there was a price.
Vietnam as much as anything led to the development of a hard, and to some
extent extra-parliamentary, left which was to plague the party for at least
the next 15 years.
Those around at the time can recall the enthusiasm which surrounded Wilson's
first victory in 1964. He seemed the voice of the new Britain; classless,
interested in technology, planning and economic growth. Pimlott explains
this in terms of big ideas: the National Plan and the new Department of
Economic Affairs. When economic growth proved a chimera, the plan collapsed
and so did Wilsonism. Thereafter he became a prime minister under siege or,
as Wilson later put it himself, someone primarily interested in keeping the
ship afloat. Hindsight suggests that we should be more kind to him than were
some of his contemporaries. Only Margaret Thatcher has subsequently done
better, and even her achievements are subject to review.
Pimlott's book is not perfect, partly because he has not finally formed his
own judgment. He is sometimes too hostile to the ambitious young Wilson,
then unduly sympathetic to the prime minister in his dog days. Yet without
the ambition Wilson would never have arrived in the first place.
The book is also uneasily poised between journalism and history: too much on
scandals like Profumo, not enough detached assessment. Although 811 pages
may seem long, too much is missed out: it is not a chronicle of the time.
But it does contain new detail, like Wilson's alliance with Enoch Powell
during the 1974 election. And it reminds us of some marvellous quotes, such
as Wilson being asked what he would miss most on leaving 10 Downing Street
in 1970: 'Mainly the job.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 18
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-10770</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJ2B8ADSFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Perilous ascent from the pit: After last month's economic
battering, the Amato government is coming to grips with Italy's problems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Quite suddenly the government of Prof Giuliano Amato has recovered its nerve
after being so rudely battered by last month's lira devaluation.
The language of disaster has receded as the floating lira has stabilised
amid calmer foreign exchange markets. The 1993 budget, essential for the
government's international credibility and commitment to tackle Italy's
public finances, has passed its stiffest test in parliament, and the fragile
four-party government coalition is holding. In response, the Bank of Italy
lowered the discount rate 1 percentage point to 14 per cent on Monday, and
the exceptionally high rates charged by the banks to industry have begun to
ease.
'We have been right at the bottom of the pit,' says Mr Piero Barucci, the
Italian Treasury minister. 'Now we are grappling our way out and are just
holding onto the edge.'
As a professional banker, he is too cautious to believe Italy's financial
crisis has been resolved. The overall economic backdrop of Italy struggling
to meet the targets of convergence laid down by the Maastricht treaty
remains uncertain. No date has been fixed for the lira's re-entry into the
European Monetary System; the inflationary effects of the September
devaluation (at present 15 per cent against the D-Mark) will take time to
filter through the economy; and the worst of recession may still come.
However, an important turning point has been reached. The 54-year-old
Socialist prime minister has devoted all his energy during his four months
in office to formulating economic policy and getting it accepted by
parliament. The emphasis now shifts towards the execution of this policy,
while fleshing out the complex details of the government's ambitious
privatisation programme. This may be a more leisurely challenge, but no less
difficult.
All the more so because both the government and the political establishment
have to address the three other priority areas outlined by Prof Amato when
he took office - electoral and institutional reform, cleaning up public
morality and the fight against organised crime.
While attention has focused on Italy's financial crisis, the country has
been going through some profound changes. The postwar structure of political
parties is breaking up and new alliances are in the air. The Christian
Democrats and Socialists, the two principal partners of the present
four-party coalition, risk disintegration if they fail to re-establish their
credibility. The unity of the Italian state is being challenged by a revolt
in the north, championed by the populist Lombard League which opposes paying
taxes to support what it views as corrupt government in Rome and an
unproductive south.
At the same time, the role of the state is set to undergo a sea-change:
welfare benefits are being cut while the public sector is about to be
slimmed down, partly through privatisation, and removed from the ravages of
political patronage.
'Economic reform is moving faster in this turbulence than political change.
This is because everyone has been forced to confront the problem of our
national debt,' observes a leading Italian economist. Indeed, debt has been
at the root of the current turmoil. At more than 10.5 per cent of GDP, it is
nearly three times the European Community average. Interest charges this
year will be the equivalent of the entire 1992 budget deficit, now projected
at L160,000bn (Pounds 74bn).
From the outset Prof Amato has said bluntly that there is no alternative to
austerity and a fundamental shake-up of public spending, whatever the
complexion of the government. His message has sunk home. The political
consensus on the broad lines of economic and financial policy is much
greater than might appear from the statements of those outside the
government. The absence of credible alternatives has enabled an otherwise
weak government to survive with a 16-seat majority in the lower house of
parliament. Proposals to reform pensions, health, local administration and
the civil service were approved last week in record time.
Although the government resorted to votes of confidence to accelerate the
debate, the opposition was centred far more on the limits placed on the
legislative role of parliament than on the content of the reforms. Together,
these reforms will provide a third of the extra L93,000bn needed to hold the
public sector deficit in 1993 at its current level. According to Prof Franco
Reviglio, the budget minister, this is the first attempt to incorporate
structural changes in spending into the annual budget.
The success of the reforms will depend on an improvement in Italy's poorly
motivated and exceptionally bureaucratic civil service. More immediate will
be the impact of increased income, corporate and property taxes, spending
cuts and the freeze on public sector employment expected to be approved by
parliament within the next two weeks. These measures will account for the
bulk of the remaining revenue in the 1993 budget.
The most controversial reform is the government's move to crack down on tax
evasion by the 6.1m people classified as self-employed by taxing them on
computerised estimates of real earnings. The move would, on average, double
the earnings on which the self-employed would be liable for tax.
To make the point, the Finance Ministry has leaked details of a study of
62,000 tax returns of which 90 per cent were shown to be unacceptably low.
One-third declared taxable income of less than L7.2m. The proposed 'minimum
tax' has provoked outraged protest from those affected. But wider public
sympathy could be limited at a time when everyone is being asked to make
sacrifices.
The revolt against the minimum tax has thrown a further unpredictable
element into the fortunes of the two main parties in government, the
Christian Democrats and Socialists. The degree of their public discredit and
internal division is profound and accelerating.
The worst damage has been done by the eight-month-old investigations of
Milan magistrates into municipal corruption on public works contracts, which
has sparked a countrywide drive to uncover illegal funding of political
parties. Now at least 70 members of parliament, mainly Christian Democrat
and Socialist but also members of the former Communist party of the
Democratic Left (PDS) and Republicans, are under investigation for
corruption and bribe-taking.
The picture which is emerging is that of systematic corruption at the local,
regional and national levels, whereby a high percentage of all public works
contracts over the past decade were handed out on the basis of rigged deals,
with 5 per cent commissions going into the pockets of the main political
parties. Political commentators estimate that L4,000bn a year is being
raised in this fashion, supporting some 80,000 bureaucrats in the
infrastructure of the main parties.
The corruption investigations will increase pressure on the parties to find
more transparent forms of finance, to reduce radically the numbers on their
payroll and to curb patronage politics at the state's expense. Equally
important has been the confirmation by Palermo magistrates of what has long
been suspected - the Christian Democrats have enjoyed close links with the
mafia, tacitly permitting organised crime to flourish in southern Italy in
return for votes.
The discredited nomenklatura of the Christian Democrat party, epitomised by
stalwarts such as Mr Arnaldo Forlani and Mr Giulio Andreotti, the former
prime minister and supreme deal-maker for three decades, has been forced to
the side lines this month. Mr Mino Martinazzoli, the new secretary-general,
has promised to clean the stables and find a new direction. But the party's
perennial appeal as an anti-communist front has evaporated with the end of
the cold war.
Mr Bettino Craxi still clings to the leadership of the Socialists but he has
been seriously weakened by the corruption scandal in his fiefdom of Milan.
He is being challenged by Mr Claudio Martelli, the ambitious justice
minister and Craxi's former protege. The party could split at any moment.
Both parties were savaged by voters in last month's regional elections in
the northern city of Mantua. Voters there gave more than a third of their
support to Mr Bossi's Lombard League. The league is still riding the wave of
anti-Rome sentiment in the north despite some erratic gestures, including an
unsuccessful call for its supporters to boycott the purchase of Treasury
bills, which the party sees as financing irresponsible public spending.
Some politicians such as Mr Giorgio La Malfa, leader of the small Republican
party, believe the only way to counter the Lombard's appeal in the north and
centre of the country is to form a new alliance or alliances across the
traditional parties. This is already beginning to take shape in talks
involving Mr Mario Segni, the reformist Christian Democrat, Mr Martelli and
his Socialist supporters, elements in the PDS and the Republicans. Mr Segni
and Mr La Malfa, both sons of prominent politicians, are among the most
visible of the new generation of Italian politicians. Their claims to lead
the next government depend in good measure on the success or failure of Prof
Amato.
Once the 1993 budget is finalised next month, the extent to which political
alliances have shifted could become clearer. But the real problem
confronting Italy's politicians is how long the present government, which
relies on two discredited parties, should be allowed to remain in office. On
his own admission, Prof Amato sees his as a transitional administration with
a twofold task: to establish a framework for restoring Italy's finances,
allowing convergence with the rest of the EC; and to initiate reform of the
unworkable system of proportional representation.
A 60-strong commission, made up of members of the two houses of parliament,
has begun working on proposals for electoral reform, but these will not be
ready before next April. The pace is being forced by the prospect of a
series of referenda on electoral reforms which will go ahead next year if
approved by the constitutional court.
To hold elections before the reforms are in place makes little sense.
Equally, the parties have no funds at present to fight elections. However,
the longer the Amato government stays in power, the more it risks seeing the
base of its political support - the Christian Democrats and Socialists -
fragmenting. For this reason there is likely to be an increasing emphasis on
political change in the coming weeks.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
