<PROFILE>_AN-CJ2B8ADRFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Leading Article: Eastern vision
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
WHAT THE European Community desperately needs is what Mr George Bush
labelled the 'vision thing'. It is not coming from the politicians. But a
spark has come from Mr Jacques Attali, president of the European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development. What the leaders of the Czech and Slovak
republics, Hungary and Poland, in London yesterday for their first joint
summit meeting with the EC, need is action on one of Mr Attali's ideas: that
for a Continental common market.
The economic and political destiny of eastern and central Europe lies with
the west. As is noted in the European Bank's latest Quarterly Economic
Review, several countries in the region have already seen the share of the
EC markets in their exports rise from 20 to 30 per cent in 1989 to more than
50 per cent. But if eastern and central Europe must look to the west, the
west cannot afford to ignore the east. Eastern Europe now needs what the
west obtained after the second world war: integration through multilateral
trade.
Mr Attali rightly condemns the so-called 'Europe Agreements' between the EC
on one side and Czechoslovakia, Hungary and Poland, on the other. These, he
has argued, appear designed to 'restrict their access to key western markets
rather than to integrate them'. Not only are the agreements restrictive,
they are also bilateral. What is needed, instead, is a multilateral
framework binding eastern and central Europe both to western Europe and to
one another.
The EC leaders should propose a European free trade agreement or customs
union of which the European Economic Area, incorporating the EC, would be
the core. The agreement should be open to any European country committed to
the market economy and to democracy. It would offer free access to the
markets of western Europe for manufactures and movement towards free trade
in agricultural products and services. Meanwhile, safeguard mechanisms, such
as anti-dumping, should be made subject to multilateral surveillance.
This is a vision worthy of discussion at the Edinburgh summit. The EC exists
to stabilise Europe. If it tries to promote western stability while ignoring
eastern chaos, it will fail.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
