<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Survey of Hungary (7): Far right stirs up trouble -
Instability too close for comfort
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HUNGARIANS have watched ethnic war in the old Yugoslav republics, race riots
in eastern Germany, fascist pamphleting in Romania and political instability
in Poland - and thanked their lucky stars that their own country was
different.
On the surface the country remains an island of stability. But Hungary's
extreme right has risen from its slumber, bringing anti-semitism and
territorial ambition, long traditions buried under taboo, back into public
discourse.
It took little to summon up echoes from the darker side of Hungary's past:
one ranting essay damning communists for being Jews and Jews for being
communists in the party newspaper of the ruling conservatives, the Hungarian
Democratic Forum.
But the far right manifesto - turned out to be more than a laughable
throwback to the rhetoric of Hungary's fascist era. The author was Mr Istvan
Csurka, populist writer, vice-president and bad conscience of the Forum.
Support among frustrated ruling party activists for Mr Csurka's call for a
purge of the enemies of the nation is so strong as to make him well-nigh
unassailable, government officials admit.
Tellingly, the Forum's ethical committee has investigated, not Mr Csurka,
but the colleague who dared to write that the manifesto was the basis of a
complete Nazi ideology. Mr Csurka remains in place.
As for Mr Jozsef Antall, the moderate prime minister and president of the
Forum, when pressed to take a stand on the article, he could muster little
more than the adjectives 'mistaken and damaging'.
Little wonder. Mr Antall, whose government has managed to push through vital
legislation needed to transform Hungary's economy and institutions, has too
many battles on other fronts to invite another.
The prime minister faces open disaffection among the Forum's liberals, few
though they are, and from his fractious coalition partners, the more loyal
of which last month declared itself the opposition within.
Voters are turning against the Forum in the opinion polls and by-elections.
After 45 years of communism, Hungary needs time to build up a middle class
and broader civil society large and confident enough to provide a secure
base for democratic government.
The liberal professional class came out on to the streets in a peaceful
protest against Mr Csurka and his friends, and western opinion, in which the
government has often sought consolation, has also shown dismay at the
government's appeasement of the far right.
Even some of the prime minister's closest aides, who liked to boast that
Hungary had a natural conservatism that would keep them in power for
decades, now privately resign themselves to defeat at the next elections in
1994.
The perceived state of the economy is another reason for Hungarian
democracy's 'feelbad factor'. Output from the large state enterprises has
declined by a fifth over the past three years, and rising unemployment has
made people cut back on consumption.
For others - and the government's supporters number heavily among them  -
the sharper frustration is that former communists are not sharing the
economic suffering, but turning adeptly into capitalists and prospering.
'They have forgotten Marx and only remember Das Capital,' the prime minister
likes to jibe.
To understand the gall, go to the provinces, says a prime ministerial aide,
and see 'the smiling, self-satisfied faces' of those communists who have
made the transition. A lot of Hungarians want to wipe away that smile. They
voted in the government to do that; it has failed them, and they are angry.
Mr Csurka articulated that feeling - and much more.
The government could push for satisfying purges but only by jeopardising the
stability Mr Antall needs, and undermining vital economic recovery in the
process.
The unpalatable truth is that Hungary's communists were by the final decade
communist only in name and careerists in practice. They have acquired by
default a wealth of experience, and the economy can ill do without them.
The prime minister's circle puts the dilemma as a choice between efficiency
and justice, and by and large it is justice that has fallen by the wayside.
The trouble is that the government is not looking very efficient either. Nor
is it likely to, with the recession postponing recovery to 1993 and beyond.
'Next year is already too close to the elections,' admits one adviser close
to the prime minister. 'Even if there is GDP growth, it will be too slow and
easy to dispute.'
One prime-ministerial aide says that the 'national versus cosmopolitan'
issue will inevitably be one of the main factors in the political fight over
the next 18 months. In itself, that would not be enough to save the Forum
government. It would probably need what one official close to the government
described as the 'Falklands factor', recalling how Mrs Margaret Thatcher,
the former UK Prime Minister, swept to electoral victory on a wave of
patriotic fervour after the Falklands war.
The prime minister is anything but the sabre-rattling type, but there are
others in his party who would not be so squeamish about playing the
nationalist card to save their political careers.
With every far right outburst and regional crisis, Mr Antall's dilemma
tightens. The fates of his party, his government and his country, which Mr
Antall often seemed to consider one and the same, are increasingly out of
line; and the time is coming closer when the prime minister will have to
choose.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 33
</PAGE>
</DOC>
