<DOCNO>FT924-10774</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJ2B8ADOFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Survey of Hungary (6): Reserves of strength - The external
accounts are in good shape
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE clearest indicator of Hungary's readiness to embark on a new path of
sustained economic growth is to be found in the strength of its foreign
reserves and the reduced burden of debt. Over the past two years Hungary,
once viewed as the most indebted of the post-communist states on a per
capita basis, has built up its reserves from Dollars 1.2bn in 1990 to nearly
Dollars 6bn.
Gross debt has stabilised at just under Dollars 23bn while the combination
of a Dollars 700m current surplus over the first seven months, and the
continuing strong inflow of foreign investment funds, has allowed a Dollars
1.1bn reduction in net foreign debt to around Dollars 15bn, according to Mr
Peter Bod, governor of the newly independent central bank, the Hungarian
National Bank.
As a result Hungary's gross debt service ratio has dropped from 63 per cent
in 1990 to around 38 per cent this year. It is forecast to drop to between
31/33 per cent in 1993.
This dramatic improvement in the external accounts is partly a reflection of
the collapse in rouble-denominated trade with the former Comecon area.
Although Hungary still imports most of its diminishing requirements of oil
and gas from the former Soviet Union at dollar prices, resources formerly
dedicated to rouble area exports are now more efficiently and profitably
deployed supplying OECD, and especially EC markets.
Hungary also no longer has to pay hard currency for components incorporated
into Hungarian goods sold on Comecon markets for roubles. This and the lower
real incomes of many poorer Hungarians, has contributed to slack import
demand.
Over the first seven months of this year exports to the EC rose by 21 per
cent compared with a 14 per cent increase in exports overall. In September,
according to Mr Bela Kadar, the foreign trade minister, exports to the EC
exceeded 50 per cent of the total for the first time. This, he points out,
already takes Hungary over the sought after 'integration threshold' which
has to be passed if aspirations for full EC membership before the turn of
the century, are to be realised.
Current levels of exports to the EC compare with the 14 per cent share of
Hungary's exports to the Community in the 1970's and a 25 per cent average
in the 1980's. Traditionally food exports have been high on the list of
exports to EC markets and freer access granted by the EC association
agreement signed earlier this year has helped to boost food exports by 10
per cent.
But with over 60 per cent of all foreign investment going into the
manufacturing and engineering sectors, Hungary looks well placed to increase
its penetration of EC industrial markets.
Thanks largely to its early start with semi-market reforms in the late
1960's, Hungary already managed to attract Dollars 570m in foreign
investment between 1972 and 1989. This experience facilitated its leap to
the top of the post-communist foreign investment league in 1990 when it
attracted Dollars 900m. The equity inflow into privatisation and greenfield
investment projects rose to Dollars 1.56bn in 1991 and amounted to Dollars
740m over the first half of this year. To date over half the total foreign
investment in post-communist east and central Europe has flowed into this
country.
For the average Hungarian, however, the bulging coffers of the National Bank
of Hungary are merely a tantalizing reflection of the scale of the sacrifice
of living standards demanded for future growth. This is politically
unsustainable and skirmishing is already mounting with 1994 elections in
view.
Export-led growth will remain the underlying priority. But Hungary no longer
needs to add to reserves and can afford a more expansive, domestic economic
policy. The IMF's requirement that the budget deficit is reduced to within 6
per cent of GDP will ensure that reflating the domestic economy starts
cautiously. But industrial output is already perking up after two traumatic
years for the old-style public sector economy.
Output from the dominant state sector dropped nearly 45 per cent from 1988
levels but hit bottom in May and is now showing tentative signs of recovery.
Output from the dynamic, but still largely unrecorded private sector, is
rising sharply but its growth is not yet strong enough to absorb
unemployment which has soared from one to 11.1 per cent over the past two
years.
Next year's expected rise in domestic output and consumption will raise
imports and probably reduce the strong current account surpluses of the past
two years. But reserves and exports are now strong enough to sustain a
politically necessary rise in domestic output and income.
This year has already seen the first clear benefit from foreign investment.
Mr Kadar estimates that around 15 per cent of Hungarian exports over the
first half of this year came from newly established foreign companies such
as General Electric and Elektrolux and many other smaller companies among
the 13,000 foreign joint ventures formed to date. This proportion is
expected to rise smartly as export production builds up at the car and
engine plants built by General Motors, and the other investments such as
Suzuki and Ford.
Foreign companies have invested over Dollars 4bn and are playing a crucial
role in bringing Hungary's productive capacity up to world standards. But
they are also looking forward to rising domestic incomes and demand. Only
when this starts rising will the newcomers benefit, as suppliers to the
growing domestic market and as exporters from this stable and low cost base.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 33
</PAGE>
