<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / International Company News: Nestle shows interest in buying
parts of SME
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NESTLE, the Swiss-based multinational foods group, yesterday gave the first
clear signal of interest in acquiring parts of SME, Italy's state-controlled
foods, retailing and catering concern.
Mr Francois Xavier Perroud, a Nestle spokesman, said: 'We are watching this
with undisguised interest. I can't exclude some parts of SME could fit well
with our existing activities'.
However, he declined to comment on whether negotiations were taking place.
Rumours of a purchase by Nestle, or other leading European foods groups,
have driven up shares in SME, which is 62 per cent owned the IRI state
holding company, in Milan in recent days.
The stock, which has surged by 40 per cent in the past two months, yesterday
climbed by 2.35 per cent to L4,849. On Tuesday, SME was suspended for the
day after Consob, Italy's companies and stock market watchdog, demanded
information from IRI about its plans.
SME is one of Italy's biggest food producers, with sales of L2,323bn
(Dollars 1.74bn) last year. The remaining turnover derives from retailing -
L2,478bn in 1991 - mainly through the GS supermarket chain, while catering
sales amounted to L1,01bn.
Any acquirer would probably concentrate on SME's branded foods. Its Bertolli
vegetable oils and Cirio canned vegetables brands are household names in
Italy.
Cirio and associated companies are undisputed leaders in the L1,100bn
Italian tomato products market, with a share of almost 28 per cent.
SME has also consolidated its position abroad. It claims over 24 per cent of
the L370bn US olive oil market and substantial presences in France and Spain
for processed tomato products.
In replies to Consob, IRI and SME both denied negotiations on the sale of
all or part of the group. However, IRI's severe debt problems have spurred
speculation about a possible disposal. This week, Ferruzzi, the Italian
agro-industrial group, confirmed its interest in SME, while spokesmen for Mr
Raul Gardini, the former Ferruzzi head now building an independent foods
empire, indicated he may also be interested in expanding his activities.
By contrast, Ifil, the investment concern controlled by Fiat's Agnelli
family, which has been expanding its food activities, yesterday denied any
interest in SME, as did BSN, the French foods group.
</TEXT>
