<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / International Company News: UAP profits slide to FFr948m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNION des Assurances de Paris (UAP), France's largest insurance group,
yesterday announced an unexpectedly steep 59 per cent fall in interim
profits and a FFr1bn recapitalisation of Banque Worms, its troubled banking
subsidiary.
The combination of the sharp fall in profits - from FFr2.34bn in the first
six months of 1991 to FFr948m (Dollars 184.07m) in the same period this year
 -and the announcement of the terms of Banque Worms' recapitalisation
depressed UAP's shares.
Mr Jean Peyrelevade, chairman, added to the gloom by saying that he did not
anticipate an improvement for the second half.
The announcement comes only a few weeks after Assurances Generales de
France, another large insurer, announced that its profits had fallen in the
first half. French insurers have been affected by intense competition and
the impact of the economic slowdown on industrial investments and property
holdings.
UAP was also hit by the performance of Banque Worms, which posted an interim
loss of FFr350m. The group announced in July that it planned to recapitalise
Banque Worms, which has suffered from a fall in the value of its property
portfolio and investments, but analysts had anticipated a smaller injection
of perhaps FFr600m to FFr700m.
Mr Peyrelevade said UAP was cutting overheads and broadening its business
base in an attempt to return to profits growth. The group increased turnover
by 22 per cent from FFr53.8bn to FFr65.6bn in the first half, but this was
largely due to the contribution from Sun Life in the UK.
