</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / International Company News: SKF slumps to SKr361m loss after
nine months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BROWN-HUMES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SWEDEN'S SKF, the world's leading roller bearing manufacturer, sank to a
SKr361m (Dollars 62.56m) loss in the first nine months.
The result, which compares with a SKr85m profit a year ago and is worse than
expected, reflects a sharp deterioration in third-quarter sales in the
group's main European markets and a big loss at Ovako, the special steels
operation which it bought last year.
It means the group will make a sizeable loss this year, with continued
losses forecast for the final three months, upsetting the prediction of a
1992 profit which it made at the six-month stage.
As a result, SKF will intensify its efforts to reduce costs, with a further
3,000 job losses projected in 1993 on top of the 10,000 which have been cut
since 1990.
Group sales in the first nine months fell to SKr19.99bn from SKr20.07bn a
year ago. The company said sales to the European car industry, which had
shown a positive trend for more than a year, deteriorated. 'All forecasts
for the European car and truck industry point to a further reduction in
sales during 1993,' it added.
With Europe accounting for 60 per cent of sales, it was little consolation
that the group had better sales performances in the North American and
Asia-Pacific regions.
Ovako recorded a SKr407m loss over the nine months on sales of SKr2.30bn.
Its result reflected falling volumes and lower steel prices. A year ago,
Ovako was reported as an associate company.
'The prospects for the fourth quarter and for 1993 are grim,' said Mr John
Longhurst, European capital goods analyst at James Capel, which now expects
SKF to make a 1992 pre-tax loss of up to SKr600m, excluding redundancy
provisions. This compares with a SKr221m loss last year.
</TEXT>
