<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Survey of Hungary (4): Down on the farm
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
MULTINATIONALS are not alone in spotting the wider potential for developing
Hungary's agricultural assets. Earlier this year Danube Farms, a consortium
of UK food processors, retailers, farmers and leisure industry interests
acquired a 90-year lease on a former loss-making state farm south of
Budapest. It spreads across 22,000 acres of irrigated cropland and
traditional Hungarian puszta prairie.
Mr Mark Cherrington, the farm's managing director, is a 'hands-on' former UK
farmer and Mr Ian Chesterman, in charge of boosting vegetable production,
came from growing export vegetables in Zambia.
The six-man expatriate management team has the skill and experience to
develop the farm as a producer of high quality vegetables and dairy products
and as an industrial park for food processors. For potential investors in
these areas, says Mr Cherrington, the farm offers a 'hassle-free' entry into
the Hungarian market, with plenty of land for industrial development
available with less bureaucracy than through conventional channels such as
the State Property Agency.
The consortium also has property development and leisure industry experience
relevant to developing parts of the farm, especially around the protected
national park area of the puszta, as a rural resort.
The farm already attracts around 15,000 visitors annually for its daily
horse show and the new owners plan to expand from the existing small hotel
and traditional Hungarian horse riding centre. The consortium's plans to
develop clay pigeon shooting, golf driving facilities and a swimming pool
are expected to appeal to the growing expatriate community as well as
Hungarians.
Already, annualised output from the 1,000-strong herd of Holstein milking
cows has risen from 5,000 to around 6,500 litres per head and the cost of
winter feed has been lowered by early cropping and silaging of 24,000 tons
of maize which would have been worth much less if sold in grain form. But
the biggest changes are planned for the 10,000 arable acres where high value
niche market crops such as peas, sugar, fresh vegetables and soft fruits
will largely replace low value bulk crops such as wheat, maize and barley.
Only 200 of the original 360 workers are employed on the farm at present but
the vegetable farm alone will need about 300 workers in full operation. 'Our
main difficulty in three years' time will be finding enough workers', Mr
Cherrington says.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
