<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Survey of Hungary (3): Reforms spark a credit crunch
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LATE in 1991, the Budapest parliament passed three dry laws
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
on bankruptcy, banking and accountancy. The legislation looked so innocuous
that it slipped past without great controversy or even much consideration.
After all, the laws were taken straight from the west European book.
That missed the point. The laws have given the market economy critical mass
in Hungary and the result both shocking and sudden. 'The country is going
through a big bang,' says Mr Gyorgy Suranyi, who was president of the
National Bank of Hungary when the laws were being drafted.
The irony is that Hungary's conservative government, which came to power on
a platform of gradual reform, appears to have sleep-walked into the big bang
that it always decried. 'It was an absolutely unintentional move - but a
good one,' says Mr Suranyi.
The bankruptcy act gave companies a legal duty to declare their insolvency
and shut down loss-making activities.
At the same time, the law on financial institutions obliged banks to make
provisions against doubtful loans, allowed them to write off the sums
against tax and set exacting international standards for capital adequacy.
The final piece was the new regulation of accounting practices which allowed
companies to depreciate investment far more rapidly than before.
This cocktail, whose plain ingredients disguised its punch, has brought the
balance sheet burdens of Hungarian banks and companies into the open - and
dumped them on the government's lap.
Gain there may be someday, but for the moment the finance ministry at least
is feeling the pain. The wave of bankruptcies that hit this spring has had a
direct effect on government tax revenues. More significant is the knock-on
effect of insolvency.
Banks have provisioned heavily against non-performing assets at the expense
of their taxable profits and the state budget. Policymakers reckon the
authorities will be lucky to collect an eighth of the Ft60bn planned for
1992 in revenue from banks. To make things worse, the new depreciation
allowances for companies have cut the yield from corporation tax.
The outcome: a budget deficit which soared past the 1992 target of Ft70bn
after just four months, broke Hungary's accord with the International
Monetary Fund, and is heading towards Ft200bn or 7 per cent of GDP by
year-end.
Even that figure is obtained only with an accounting trick which flatters
Hungary's state finances: the government pays interest at well below market
levels on funds it has borrowed from the central bank.
While stimulating domestic demand, the budget deficit has halted the fall in
interest rates and threatens to crowd out any substantial recovery in
investment.
In any case, the rates which apply to companies have proved sticky
downwards. The financial reforms come into play again here. Banks, desperate
to build up reserves, have brought down lending rates far more slowly than
deposit rates to the point that spreads approach 10 per cent.
That is when the banks lend at all. They are busy also reducing lending to
meet capital adequacy requirements and because they have been burnt by
bankruptcy among clients. Hungary is in the middle of a credit crunch that
puts the western variety to shame.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
