<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / International Capital Markets: Sir Leon Brittan joins row
over capital standards - IOSCO Conference
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Leon Brittan, vice-president of the European Commission, yesterday
became involved in the growing row between financial regulators over capital
requirements for banks and securities firms.
Sir Leon criticised remarks which Mr Richard Breeden, chairman of the US
Securities and Exchange Commission, had made in an interview with the
Financial Times on Tuesday. Mr Breeden had warned that a recently-adopted EC
capital adequacy directive (or CAD) was unsafe. Sir Leon denied this last
night: 'It is certainly not as some have claimed unsafe.'
In a further attack on Mr Breeden's refusal to agree to Iosco's proposal for
a common international capital standard, Sir Leon said: 'In today's global
markets, no single national regulator . . . can expect to impose their
system on everyone else'.
Mr Breeden was also criticised by Mr Andrew Large, the chairman of the UK's
Securities and Investments Board, who said he did not think it was proper
for Mr Breeden to cast aspersions against the capital standards of other
countries.
His remarks were made after an emergency meeting of Iosco's technical
committee, which was called to discuss the widening gulf between the SEC and
other securities regulators on a new international standard which would
establish a minimum capital level to be maintained by securities firms.
Some regulators had been hopeful that three years of negotiations on the
capital standard might be close to conclusion. They had not been aware of Mr
Breeden's fundamental objections, they said.
However, the SEC said last night it was baffled by the reaction of other
regulators: 'We have been consistent for three years', an official said.
No agreement is possible without the consent of the SEC, since it is
regulator of the world's biggest securities market in the US.
The dispute between the SEC and other regulators centres on the amount of
capital which securities firms should hold to cover the risk of losses on
equity portfolios. The SEC wants a securities firms to maintain a high
minimum capital level, along the lines of rules in force in the US.
The SIB wants a formula which would encourage securities firms to hedge
their equity portfolios by using netting techniques. The SIB believes that
netting - in its simplest form offsetting a holding of shares with a
matching contract to sell other shares - reduces the risks faced by
securities firms.
It argues that the SEC's proposed amendments to the Iosco draft standard
would discourage securities firms from using netting techniques.
Mr Jean Saint-Geours, chairman of France's Commission des Operations de
Bourse, who takes over as head of Iosco's technical committee tomorrow,
suggested a new approach to capital adequacy discussions which could allow
different capital rules to apply to shares from different countries.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 28
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-10789</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJ2B8AC9FT</PROFILE>
