<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Government Bonds: Gilts spurred on by stronger sterling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UK GOVERNMENT bonds enjoyed a strong rally, spurred on by sterling's
firmness in the foreign exchanges, and gained up to a point at the long end.
The pound strengthened to DM2.4269, from DM2.4207 late on Tuesday in London.
Dealers said the market received a further lift in the afternoon following
comments from Mr Robin Leigh-Pemberton, governor of the Bank of England.
The governor stressed the need to aim for non-inflationary growth and said
that the Chancellor of the Exchequer's 1.0 per cent to 4.0 per cent target
range for inflation was likely to be met assuming Britain kept a tight
fiscal stance.
Dealers added that the calmer political climate also contributed to the
market's buoyant mood. The 9 per cent gilt due 2008 yesterday rose to 103
1/8 from 102 3/32 at Tuesday's close. In the futures market, the Liffe gilt
futures contract climbed from 100.17 to a high of 101.09 before ending at
101.04.
US Treasury prices eased slightly yesterday afternoon after firming in the
morning in the wake of Tuesday's gains.
In late trading, the benchmark 30-year bond was down  7/32 at 95 15/32 ,
yielding 7.631 per cent. The two-year note was down  1/16 at 99 27/32 ,
yielding 4.333 per cent.
The decline was attributed to profit-taking following the afternoon Treasury
auction of Dollars 10.75bn in five-year notes at a stop-out rate of 5.84 per
cent.
Dealers and investors were pleased with the market's resilience on Tuesday
in the face of a much better-than-expected third-quarter GDP report, and
follow-through buying in early trading yesterday kept prices firm. Analysts
said that Tuesday's performance suggested the market may have found a
temporary floor.
Sentiment was also buoyed by news of a 0.7 per cent rise in consumer
spending and personal income in September. Excluding special fators, the
figures were consistent with sluggish economic growth and pointed to
continued weakness during the final quarter.
DISAPPOINTMENT over the Bundesbank's decision to leave the repo rate
unchanged yesterday pushed German government bond prices lower in the
morning, but the market later recovered to end firmer on the day. The
central bank left the rate for securities repurchase agreements unchanged in
its latest money market operations, dashing hopes of a cut in the key
interest rates at today's Bundesbank council meeting.
The central bank injected DM11.4bn of liquidity at its allocation of 14-day
repos, leaving the lowest accepted repo rate unchanged at 8.75 per cent. The
Liffe bund futures contract rose from 91.48 to trade at around 91.61 by late
afternoon.
HOPES of an easing in interest rates lifted Japanese government bonds with
both the cash and futures markets reaching new highs.
The December futures contract rose from its opening of 107.25 to end at
107.36, the high of the day. In the cash market, the yield on the No 145
issue moved from 4.755 per cent at the opening to end at 4.725 per cent.
Dealers said investors were hoping to see an easing in interest rates this
week in conjunction with the quarterly meeting of the Bank of Japan's branch
managers.
