<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / International Capital Markets: UK rules on insider dealing
attacked - ISOCO Conference
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK government's proposed legislation on insider dealing was attacked
yesterday at the International Organisation of Securities Commissions
(Iosco) conference by Mr Paul Myners, chairman of Gartmore Investment
Management, writes Norma Cohen.
The directive, as proposed, defines inside information as any which 'may
affect a company's business prospects'. It is intended to correspond to a
more vaguely-worded European Community directive barring insider trading. Mr
Myners said that that proposal leaves far too ambiguous a definition to
enable fund managers and securities analysts to do their jobs.
'I believe that, unless these uncertainties are addressed by a more focused
definition, we are likely to make the job of the securities analyst and
portfolio manager almost impossible to perform,' he said. 'Uncertainties
about what constitutes insider dealing are unacceptable,' he added.
Mr Myners also pointed out several obstacles to a genuine cross-border
business in investment management, both within the EC and further afield.
First, inconsistencies in accounting conventions and access to information
have hampered genuine cross-border investments because analysts in one
country cannot easily understand the value of companies in others.
He noted that under UK accounting, pharmaceuticals company SmithKline
Beecham has negative net worth of Pounds 300m while under US accounting
rules its shareholder funds are Pounds 3.5bn. 'This is a nonsense and
something must be done about it,' he said. Also, French and German companies
regularly make use of provisions and extraordinary items to smooth earnings,
he added.
See International Capital Markets
</TEXT>
