<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / International Capital Markets: Sakura Bank to cut staff by
10%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT THOMSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SAKURA Bank, a leading Japanese commercial bank, plans to reduce its staff
by more than 10 per cent over the next three years as part of a streamlining
programme to boost long-term profitability.
The bank will also close or consolidate about 50 of its 620 branches, cut
advertising costs by 20 per cent and trim directors' salaries by 10 per cent
under the three-year programme, which was applauded by the Ministry of
Finance.
Japanese banks are generally attempting to streamline after excesses of the
late 1980s, but the task has been more difficult for Sakura, formerly Mitsui
Taiyo Kobe Bank, which was formed in 1990 after a merger between Mitsui Bank
and Taiyo Kobe Bank.
Sakura said that it would not resort to sackings to cut the number of
employees from 23,000 to 20,000, but would sharply reduce the annual
graduate intake in the spring and would not replace staff who leave.
The ministry has urged the banking industry to increase profitability to
cope with the rising total of non-performing loans arising from the late
1980s.
The ministry is expected to announce shortly a new figure of around
Y12,000bn (Dollars 98bn) for the industry's non-performing loans, up from
the Y8,000bn at the end of March.
Japanese banks are in the final stages of drafting a proposal to establish a
company to purchase non-performing loans and land collateral from afflicted
banks in an attempt to reduce the bad debt burden and stimulate the property
market.
The banks, conscious of widespread opposition to the use of public funds to
support the new company, say they are not seeking special tax concessions
for the write-off of these loans, although they have negotiated with the
finance ministry about such concessions.
Hokuriku Bank, a leading regional institution, also announced a streamlining
plan yesterday which includes a 10 per cent cut in its workforce of 4,500 by
fiscal 1995 and a sharp reduction in new spending on computer systems.
The bank, like most others, has been entangled in the collapse of various
speculators, including Nanatomi, the stock and property group, which
collapsed early last year owing about Y300bn.
</TEXT>
