<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / International Company News: War of words erupts in Campbell
bid for Arnotts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ARNOTTS, the Australian biscuit-maker, yesterday accused Campbell Soup, the
US food group, of misleading shareholders in pursuit of its ADollars 8.80
(USDollars 6.28) a share hostile takeover bid.
Mr Bill Purdy, Arnotts' chairman, released a letter to Mr David Johnson,
Campbell's chief executive, challenging Campbell's claims that it had
provided advanced technology to the Australian company since taking a 32.9
per cent shareholding in 1985.
Campbell is seeking a further 17.2 per cent shareholding, which would give
it control of Arnotts, at a cost of ADollars 209m. The bid, which is subject
to regulatory approval, values Arnotts at ADollars 1.2bn.
'Since Campbell Soup became a substantial shareholder in Arnotts, Campbell
has given us no technology or other benefits of material assistance to
Arnotts in its development either in Australia or internationally,' Mr Purdy
said.
Mr Purdy also dismissed Campbell's claims that Arnotts requires its
assistance to expand into Asia. He said Arnotts had appointed
representatives in three Asian countries, and was 'well advanced' in three
others.
'We could undertake our Asian strategy with a range of partners. We are
certainly not dependent upon Campbell Soup for our Asian strategy,' he said.
Campbell, which yesterday released its official takeover document, said it
intended to use Arnotts to penetrate Asian markets as part of its plans to
build a global biscuit business.
The group said it would assist the Australian company with technology,
marketing expertise and infra-structure.
The focus of the takeover battle shifts to a Sydney hotel today when Arnotts
holds its annual meeting.
</TEXT>
