<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / International Company News: Ford of Europe plunges into loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORD's European automotive operations plunged into a loss of Dollars 479m in
the third quarter after struggling back into profit in the first half of
1992.
The return to loss is a severe setback for Ford of Europe, which suffered a
record loss last year and which has slipped from fourth to fifth place in
the west European new car market in the first nine months this year.
Mr Harold Poling, Ford chairman, said the 'uncertainty resulting from the
instability in European currency markets has led to lower sales in most of
Ford's European markets and will continue to affect the operating
environment for the near-term'.
Ford's European car sales have declined by about 6 per cent in the first
nine months this year, which has depressed its market share to an estimated
11.6 per cent from 12.1 per cent a year ago.
Jaguar, its UK luxury car subsidiary, suffered a loss of just over Dollars
100m in the third quarter, while Ford of Britain's financial performance
deteriorated sharply in the third quarter in the face of continuing weak UK
new car sales and further heavy discounting.
Jaguar lost around Dollars 300m in the first nine months this year, although
its deficit in the third quarter was slightly lower than in the
corresponding period a year ago.
The loss of Dollars 479m on Ford's European automotive operations in the
third quarter compares with a profit of Dollars 108m in the first six months
this year and a loss of Dollars 560m in the same quarter a year ago.
Ford of Europe's automotive operations, including Jaguar, slumped to a net
loss in the whole of last year of Dollars 1.079bn from a net profit of
Dollars 145m in 1990 and a profit of Dollars 1.19bn in 1989.
In the first nine months this year, Ford's European automotive operations
lost Dollars 371m, against a loss of Dollars 765m in the corresponding
period a year ago.
Ford of Europe is being forced to cut production at most of its assembly
plants in the UK, Germany, Belgium and Spain, to reduce excessive stocks.
</TEXT>
