<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Low margins, high returns: How the group made more money
from level sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The most striking aspect of Marks and Spencer's interim results yesterday
was its ability to raise profits on a static sales base.
Sir Richard Greenbury, chairman and chief executive of Marks and Spencer,
gave four reasons:
Lower operating costs largely as a result of last year's redundancy
programme.
Substantial investments in information and operational systems resulting in
higher staff productivity.
Improved information systems giving the company better stock control,
thereby reducing the number of goods to be sold cheaper in end-of-season
sales. Emphasis on everyday low prices, generating consistent sales and
helping to ensure that a 'dramatically higher' proportion of goods was sold
at full price.
These greater operating efficiencies have enabled M and S to hold, and in
some cases reduce, the prices of its autumn clothing range without
sacrificing net profit.
'We are not conducting a once-and-for-all promotion. We intend to carry on
with it. We can run the business on this new lower gross margin and continue
to make a satisfactory profit,' Sir Richard said.
However, although the company's 18 per cent share of the clothing market
allows it to benefit from enormous economies of scale, it is not able to
repeat the trick to the same extent in foods where it only has a 3.5 per
cent market share and is coming under increasing pressure from highly
aggressive competitors.
'We cannot compete with Sainsbury's and Tesco. We are nothing more than a
large niche food retailer. Our foods business continues to be profitable and
more than pays its way. But where we are dominant in prepared and
high-quality fresh foods we are still doing very well,' Sir Richard said.
M and S's results provoked a mixed response in the City. Ms Kimlan Cook, at
County NatWest, said the company's share price had had a strong run over the
past year and at a 45 per cent premium to the market was 'starting to look
rather full'. 'Even quality has its price,' she said.
However, Mr Quintin Price, retailing analyst at stockbrokers James Capel,
said: 'I am amazed that the market has marked the shares down so far. In an
incredibly hostile environment M and S has raised earnings per share by more
than 20 per cent. It is a back-handed compliment that people expected more.'
