<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Marks and Spencer profits rise 20%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MARKS and Spencer, the clothing and food retailer, yesterday demonstrated
its continued dominance of the UK high street by posting a 20 per cent
improvement in interim pre-tax profits to Pounds 257.1m.
The rise was flattered by the absence of any exceptional charges, which
depressed the previous year's figure by Pounds 16.9m. But even excluding
this factor, profits were still 11 per cent up as the company squeezed
higher net profits from near-static sales.
Sir Richard Greenbury, chairman and chief executive, said: 'We are now
running the business more efficiently than we have for many years and
therefore need a lower gross margin, passing the benefits of that on to the
customer in terms of better-value goods.'
However, the City was worried by the company's flat UK sales and the
cautious stance on current trading. It was also disappointed with the 5 per
cent rise in the interim dividend to 2.2p when earnings per share rose 22
per cent to 6.2p. The shares fell 15.5p to 327 1/2 p.
Sir Richard described the dividend payment as an 'amber light' on current
trading. 'I do not think that our dividend is anything other than prudent.
The economy does not give me a lot of hope. There is still a long hard haul
ahead,' he said.
In the half year to September 26, group turnover fell 0.3 per cent to Pounds
2.64bn. Clothing sales in the UK rose 1 per cent to Pounds 1.22bn while food
sales were only 0.4 per cent ahead at Pounds 1.02bn.
Operating profits, however, were 7 per cent higher at Pounds 253.3m as the
company widened its net profit margin from 8.9 per cent to 9.6 per cent.
Interest income, up from Pounds 1.4m to Pounds 10.1m, also boosted the
profits gain. The contribution from financial services rose from Pounds 9.5m
to Pounds 12.6m.
The group's international operations recorded a mixed trading performance.
In spite of heavy opening costs, the continental European stores increased
profits from Pounds 5.7m to Pounds 6.6m on sales up 35 per cent at Pounds
97m. Sir Richard warned that sales were beginning to soften.
The company's trauma in Canada continued although losses were reduced from
Pounds 5.8m to Pounds 700,000. Kings Supermarkets and Brooks Brothers in the
US lifted profits by Pounds 200,000 to Pounds 3.3m. The company's four Hong
Kong stores improved their contribution from Pounds 700,000 to Pounds 3.4m
but Brooks Brothers in Japan reported a weakening of sales.
