<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Tension over the future of Hong Kong deepens: UK-China
documents show difficult negotiations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALEXANDER NICOLL, Asia Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TENSION between Britain and China over the future of Hong Kong deepened
yesterday with the publication by both governments of previously secret
diplomatic exchanges on the development of democracy in the colony.
Britain took the unusual step of publishing messages which passed in 1990
between Chinese officials and Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, to back up
its denial that Britain had broken a secret agreement, as was alleged in an
angry outburst from Beijing last week.
China released the documents after hearing London would. Official news
agency Xinhua said they showed Mr Patten's proposals on elections to be held
in 1995 'run counter to the understanding reached by the Chinese and British
sides through diplomatic consultations'.
The documents concern arrangements for Hong Kong's political structure as
China neared completion of the Basic Law, Hong Kong's post-1997
constitution. They provide an insight into the difficult negotiations on
Hong Kong, which reverts to Chinese sovereignty in 1997.
Mr Hurd's attempts to win an increase in the number of directly elected
seats to the Legislative Council, the colony's parliament, were met with
frosty replies from Qian Qichen, China's foreign minister - couched in the
language of diplomacy.
Mr Chris Patten, Hong Kong's governor, said: 'What they make abundantly
plain is that there was no secret deal on the future political development
of Hong Kong between the British government and the Chinese government.'
Beijing has warned of turmoil in Hong Kong if Mr Patten pushes ahead with
his proposal that a committee, due to appoint 10 members of the Legislative
Council in 1995, should itself be popularly elected. Mr Patten proposes
broadening the voting base for other indirectly elected seats, but has not
sought more directly elected seats.
It was on the composition of the election committee that Lu Ping, the senior
Beijing official responsible for Hong Kong affairs, alleged a secret
understanding. He threatened to reverse the measures and said they
contravene the Basic Law.
In one message, Mr Hurd says: 'I agree in principle with the arrangements
for an electoral committee, which could be established in 1995.'
British officials said the committee's composition was a side issue, that
the Basic Law did not include understandings on the subject as Britain had
hoped, and that the question of 1995 electoral arrangements remained open
after the exchanges.
The focus was on directly elected seats. To a request from Mr Hurd on an
increase in these, Qian said 'the Chinese side cannot bring itself to agree
to the foreign secretary's proposal.'
Mr Hurd said if changes were not made, there would be resignations from the
executive and legislative councils.
