<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / The Lex Column: French insurers
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The 59 per cent fall in UAP's first half profits looks a dreadful
performance even by the dismal standards of its peers. But the real lesson
of yesterday's figures - and those from GAN and AGF earlier in the month -
is that the company's previous results were flattered by unsustainably high
asset values. UAP is now showing some signs of getting to grips with pricing
and concentrating its attention on profits rather than market share. Premium
increases, though, have not gone nearly far enough. The whole sector is
vulnerable to recession-related claims of the kind which have plagued the UK
domestic market if the French economy takes another downward twist next
year. The real problem, though, is unlocking some of the unrealised capital
gains which give UAP its apparent financial strength and which have
underpinned profits in the past. Two thirds of the total is tied up in land
and buildings.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
