<DOCNO>FT924-10826</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJ2B8AB6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / The Lex Column: Marks and Spencer
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Marks and Spencer's interim figures show starkly why it has bitten the
bullet on pricing in its autumn marketing campaign. While earnings per share
are up a very creditable 22 per cent, sales are flat. True, the earnings
rise is gilded because last year's figure was depressed by exceptional
items, but underlying profits growth is being fuelled by cost control and
cash management. That process must have a finite limit, however much this
recession teaches companies to find hidden fat. Hence Marks' need to get
sales moving. In these deflationary times price is the chosen weapon, and
the company is consciously hazarding margins to bring in extra sales.
The strategy of consistent low pricing will strengthen Marks' position in
the longer term. But with other retailers running near-permanent sales, it
may be difficult to get the message across meanwhile. If that proves to be
the case, Marks may not reap the extra sales to compensate for reduced
margins. The risks of losing margin and market share are just as strong in
food as they are in clothing. Like-for-like sales are under pressure at the
supermarket giants, and while Marks insists that its value-added food is not
losing out, pressure can only build as the recession continues and more
superstores open.
Despite the woes of the economy, investors should not lose sight of Marks'
fundamentally strong position. The freehold empire largely untroubled by
rental pressures, a cast iron balance sheet and a solid franchise all
support the company. The shares may dip as investors fret about the near
term outlook; the question is what kind of a premium they are prepared to
pay for such a core holding.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-10827</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJ2B8AB5FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / The Lex Column: UK accounting
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Companies and their auditors have a habit of squeezing through fresh gaps in
the accounting maze once old ones have been fenced off. But there are good
reasons to believe that the new standard known as FRS 3 will put an end to
many of the sleights of hand which confused investors in the past.
In future, for example, the impact of property write downs and currency
translation - this last so damaging to Polly Peck shareholders - will have
to be shown in a separate statement to the profit and loss account rather
than being buried away in the notes. The effect on companies' depreciation
policies where assets are revalued will also have to be highlighted. And the
turnover and profits totals will be usefully split into continuing and
discontinued operations.
From the market's point of view, though, the biggest challenge will be
grappling for a reliable measure of earnings per share. Quite rightly, the
Accounting Standards Board has given up the long and unequal struggle to
separate exceptionals from extraordinaries and has opted to throw everything
above the line. But the result may be a good deal of confusion as analysts
and investors strive to establish what they believe is the underlying trend.
There will be no single formula, but then that reflects the real world. You
would hardly strip out disposal profits for the likes of Hanson, but you
probably would exclude them in the case of a group which sells businesses
only once in a blue moon. No doubt companies, as well as publishing the
erratic figure which will flow from FRS 3, will try to massage the market
towards a number of their own. But at least they - and independent
commentators - will be arguing on the basis of fuller information. There
should be much less discretion for an auditor's judgment.
</TEXT>
