<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Management (Marketing and Advertising): Great expectations
and low profits for agencies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If advertising agencies were not already suffused with gloom, the latest
annual profitability survey* by Touche Ross will dispel any doubts that they
are facing a structural crisis every bit as profound as that being
experienced by other once-powerful UK industries.
The Touche Ross survey, published tomorrow shows that average profit margins
 -operating profit as a percentage of turnover - have fallen for the third
year (from 1.9 per cent to 1.8 per cent), the lowest for seven years.
At the same time average staff costs per head increased by 6.6 per cent,
while average gross income per head grew by only 2.9 per cent. As agencies
have become less profitable, they have also become more indebted; long term
debt increased by 15 per cent to Pounds 1.33bn. Interest costs now account
for 36 per cent of the potential pre-tax profits of the agencies, compared
with 26 per cent in the previous year's survey.
Pre-tax profits fell for all of the 13 publicly-quoted agencies, except the
media-buying CIA group; nine of those surveyed saw pre-tax profits fall by
35 per cent or more.
The survey compares the financial performances of 50 agency groups - public
and private, UK and foreign - covering December 1990 to November 1991.
Average pre-tax profits of the 50 agency groups surveyed remained unchanged,
at Pounds 3.2m; but excluding WPP - which accounted for 56 per cent of the
total pre-tax profits of all agencies in the survey - the remaining agencies
reported a fall in average pre-tax profits of 16 per cent.
The survey suggests that the larger fish - WPP, Saatchi and Saatchi, and the
Lowe Group - have increased in strength relative to some of the minnows.
Those three agencies accounted for 89 per cent of the total pre-tax profits
of the surveyed companies against 75 per cent previously.
One aspect which is bound to be closely studied is the section dealing with
aggregate operating profit per employee, down by 1 per cent to Pounds 4,882,
against an 11.5 per cent increase in 1991's survey; in 1988 the figure was
Pounds 6,029. Heading the table of gross income per employee - a key
indicator of agency strength - is Butterfield Day Devito Hockney, followed
by Geers Gross (since acquired by Publicis) and Edwards Martin Thornton.
David Miles of Touche Ross says 'a typical response among agencies (to their
financial problems) has been to reduce staff numbers but not overall levels
of reward. Expectations remain high in a sector where 'tightening one's
belt' still means something the mechanic does to the GTi convertible.'
Admittedly the survey is retrospective, but according to research**
published next week by Zenith Media, part of Saatchi and Saatchi, there is
nothing to comfort anxious agency heads in the run-up to Christmas. Instead
of the traditional rise in advertising expenditure in the final quarter,
Zenith forecasts a fall of 7 per cent in television advertising revenue.
What Zenith's forecasts appear to confirm is a double-dip in television
advertising revenues; the last quarter of 1990 registered a real decline of
10 per cent. Such advertising revenue collapses, precisely in the period
when companies normally spend the bulk of their advertising budgets, have
not been seen since 1974 (a last quarter real decline of 18 per cent) and
1969 (decline of 11 per cent).
Frank Harrison, who has carried out the research for Zenith, believes there
are two reasons for the collapse. 'Companies with foreign parents, reporting
profits in non-UK currencies, have seen their UK contribution significantly
reduced following the unforeseen withdrawal of the pound from the ERM and
its subsequent devaluation. And with the economic recession deeper and more
protracted than expected, many companies are finding it difficult to meet
profit targets for 1992 and have consequently cut back on advertising in
quarter four.'
Nor are agencies alone in their fear that the recession may now actually be
turning into slump. From January 1 1993, Channel 4 will be responsible for
selling its own air-time to advertisers; further down the road is the
projected Channel 5. Channel 4 is safeguarded to some extent: if advertising
revenues fall below 14 per cent of terrestrial net advertising revenue
(TNAR), then ITV must top up revenue to a maximum of 2 per cent of TNAR.
But without some return of consumer confidence - and willingness to spend -
advertisers will show little inclination to restore slashed marketing
budgets. The end result could be an even tighter squeeze, not just on
advertising agencies but on also some successful bidders in the ITV network,
who made their bids on very different anticipated advertising revenue
forecasts. *How Advertising Agencies Made Their Profits In 1991; available
from Nicola Toosey, Touche Ross, Hill House, 1 Little New Street, London
EC4A 3TR; 071 936 3000. Pounds 95.
** UK Television Forecasts to 2003, Zenith Media, Bridge House, 63-65 North
Wharf Road, London W2 1LA. Pounds 200 per quarter, Pounds 400 annually.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 15
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-10830</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJ2B8AB2FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / Management (Marketing and Advertising): Confounding the
image makers - The sudden bull market in US political advertising
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUREK MARTIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This has not been a predictable year for American political advertising. It
began much as it left off in 1988, as a mixture of fuzzy warmth and
below-the-belt assaults. Then along came Ross Perot and changed the rules by
taking to the 'free' television talk show circuit as, promptly, did Bill
Clinton and, much later, George Bush.
Perot disappeared for a few months and the desultory norm was renewed. Now
he is back again and paying for his own airtime at a phenomenal rate - and
at precisely the same time as the Clinton and Bush campaigns have themselves
shifted into top advertising gear.
What looked a month ago like a lean year for income from political
advertising, has now become a raging bull market. As of last week, the three
major commercial TV networks alone reported bookings of Dollars 40.9m
(Pounds 25m) from the campaigns, compared with a total of Dollars 38.5m
spent by Bush and Dukakis four years ago - and this was with the intensive
last two weeks of the campaign still to run.
Of this sum, Dollars 17.7m came from Bush, Dollars 5.5m from Clinton and
Dollars 17.3m from Perot. In one week alone, Perot bought Dollars 5.3m of
advertising time from ABC. Moreover, these figures are incomplete. They do
not include time bought on local and cable stations, where the more focused
Clinton effort has been concentrated, nor on radio, where the cheapest and
some of the dirtiest advertising has been. All told, figures of Dollars 100m
plus for spending are being talked of.
Money is not a problem. Figures this week suggest that Perot has spent about
Dollars 57m, the bulk on advertising, since he is doing virtually no
conventional campaigning, is flying in his private jet and is running only a
skeleton political organisation. According to the Federal Election
Commission last week, Clinton still had Dollars 25m cash in hand, while
Bush's reserves were even higher at Dollars 36m.
All of which would suggest that this election could turn out, even more than
four years ago, to hinge on the advertising messages being conveyed. In
reality, the notorious commercials which attacked Dukakis' supposed leniency
towards the convicted criminal Willie Horton probably only padded Bush's
margin of victory. But the lesson, practised in any number of mid-term
elections and carried over into this year, was that going for the jugular
paid dividends.
Curiously, and assuming that Perot's ad blitz does not land him in the White
House, the universal opinion is that, if anything, the reverse is true. The
most popular political programmes have been the candidate debates,
unvarnished as they are by the image makers. They attracted extraordinary
audiences of 70-95m, a testament to what may well be a serious re-awakening
of the American public's engagement in the political process.
Perot's first paid half hour 'infomercial' earlier this month, aired on one
network, was watched by no fewer than 15m people, the second most-watched
programme in its time slot, according to the ratings. Subsequent versions
have regularly out-drawn rival sitcoms. An 'infomercial' format is exactly
the same as a conventional TV programme but has the single purpose of
selling a product.
Perot's infomercial was a throwback to some ancient time of the single fixed
camera - showing just Perot at a desk, his charts and a pointer and lot of
homespun wisdom about how 'simple' solving the budget deficit can be. Other
half hours have been devoted to soft focus questioning about what a great
family man and patriot he is, an image which, by implication, would never be
conveyed by professional reporters, whom he detests.
Perot is also flooding the ether with conventional 30-second and one-minute
spots, in the first series of which he was seen in still photograph, but not
heard, letting a sonorous voice-over do the work. Later ones, blasting the
press, the pundits and the two main parties, have been directed to answering
the charge that a vote for Perot 'wasted'.
The second piece of evidence that good old attack advertising is not working
so well this year, comes from the public itself. In the second presidential
debate, in which only the public, not journalists, got to ask the questions,
the mood of the audience was crystal clear: we are fed up with smears and
character assassination and want to hear more about the issues which affect
our lives. Public opinion polls show a similar discontent.
This is a bit of a problem for the Bush campaign, with its unremittingly
negative advertisements directed at Clinton. Any British visitor remembering
the April election will quickly recognise some of them, such as the one
which portrays Clinton as a man with two blurred and 'untrustworthy' heads
and another which charges, with specific illustrations of 'ordinary' people,
that he will slap higher taxes on the middle class. A third claims that
Clinton is guilty of a 'pattern of deception,' which is now in Bush's
standard campaign speech, as is his denunciation of his opponent's record as
governor of Arkansas, which is also enshrined in a commercial.
New attack advertisements on Bush's behalf are coming out at a rapid rate.
One, aired on the morning after the second debate in St Louis, showed a
local eatery with the average Joe and Mary proclaiming that George Bush had
'won' the debate. It transpired that the location was genuine enough but
that all those giving their heartfelt opinions were local Republican
campaign workers.
The Clinton side has not been dilatory with the negative stuff, making many
a meal out of Bush's infamous pledge of 1988, 'Read my lips, no new taxes.'
Another recalls Bush saying, 'You will be better off four years from now
than you are today' and concludes, 'Well, its four years later. How're you
doing?' A third has Bush saying, 'I want a kinder, gentler . . .' and the
announcer cutting in and saying 'Uh-uh. We can't afford four more years.'
Another alleges Bush has used taxpayer money to shift US jobs to central
America. Subtle they are not.
But its reading of the public mood has also persuaded it to release more
'positive' advertising than has Bush to date. They may not be quite up to
the 'morning in America' material that was at the heart of the Reagan
re-election campaign in 1984, but they look forward to challenges with hope,
rather than backwards in anger. They never forget the economy.
Only the election will tell if all this has been money well spent. At the
start of the year many US news organisation assigned journalists to the ad
watch, on the assumption it would be influential. More now have to get up at
dawn and stay up all night for the news that is made on the talk shows.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
