<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / What the election committee letters said
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Excerpts from the British and Chinese correspondence
Douglas Hurd to Qian Qichen, Jan 18, 1990
If you wished to provide for the establishment of a grand electoral college
in the Basic Law, and the arrangements for constituting this body were open
and fully representative, we would wish to see it initiated in 1995 through
consultations between our two sides.
Hurd to Qian, January 31, 1990
It will also be important that the details of the composition and
constitution of any grand electoral college are made clear to Hong Kong
people to reassure them about the nature of their proposed future political
system. We could then consider introducing similar arrangements in 1995,
thereby ensuring continuity.
UK paper handed to Chinese government, February 6, 1990
Main aspects on which we believe agreement would be necessary are  .. size
and composition of the election committee, delineation of each category of
membership and the selection of individual members from each category  ..
procedures for the nomination and election of candidates to the legislature
 .. the following principles could best form the framework for creating an
election committee  .. it should not itself be an institution of government
 .. composition should be designed, as far as possible, to avoid direct
duplication with the membership of other constituencies returning members of
the legislature   . committee should be as representative as possible  ..
procedure for nomination  .. should be simple, open and prescribed in the
electoral law  .. voting should be by secret ballot.
Chen Ziying, China's Hong Kong and Macau Affairs Office, to British
ambassador in Beijing, February 8, 1990
With regard to the electoral committee, the Chinese side agrees with the
five principles concerning the committee proposed by the British side in the
document. However, the Chinese side maintains that the provisions on the
composition and ratio of the electoral committee as specified in  .. the
Basic Law (Draft) must be followed in terms of its proportional composition
 . China believes its provisions on composition and ratio are appropriate ..
Hurd to Qian, February 12, 1990
I agree in principle with the arrangements which you propose for an
electoral committee ..
