<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / World Trade News: Europe's gas supply lies in troubled hands
 -The fears prompted by disputes between the former Soviet Republics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY and FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A 50 per cent drop in gas supplies from Russia to western Europe last week
has raised important questions about the security of Europe's supplies as it
increases its reliance on natural gas.
The temporary drop in supplies was because of a dispute over payments
between Russia and Ukraine. Russia temporarily turned off supplies to
Ukraine and Ukraine retaliated by taking gas from the export pipeline
destined for western Europe.
Gas analysts warn the incident may seriously damage European confidence in
Russia's reliability as a supplier and prompt a rethink about where future
gas supplies should come from. Europe's choices are limited.
Changing attitudes to natural gas have brought a big increase in western
European consumption. This is mainly because of environmental considerations
and improved gas power technology.
Consumption in western Europe last year was 287bn cubic metres, according to
figures from Cambridge Energy Research Associates, the international energy
consultants. This is expected to increase by between 50 and 100 per cent by
2010.
Until the middle of the decade, Europe is likely to depend on imports from
four principal producers: Algeria, the Netherlands, Norway and the former
Soviet Union, primarily Russia.
Together these countries supply about 52 per cent of Europe's gas, but both
Norway and the Netherlands have little spare gas in the short term. That
makes Russia and Algeria the countries most likely to meet increases in
demand.
Russia already supplies more than 20 per cent of western Europe's gas needs.
It has by far the world's largest reserves - some 53,000bn cubic metres,
according to Mr Rem Vyakhirev, chairman of Gazprom, the gas industry
operator. A recent report by Moscow energy specialists predicted that gas,
even more than oil, would be the key to Russia's economic renaissance.
But those assumptions have been challenged by the recent supply problems.
One problem is that three big pipelines come together at Uzhgorod in the
Ukraine, from where the main export pipeline runs into western Europe,
giving Ukraine - which no longer enjoys the warmest of relations with
neighbouring Russia - the power to turn off supplies.
Analysts warn that any worsening of relations between the two countries  -
for example, over the disputed territory of the Crimea - could result in
Ukraine doing just that. However, Ukraine is unlikely to be able to hold
Russia to ransom for long, since it is a net importer of gas and receives
gas as payment in kind for transiting Russian gas.
A potentially more thorny problem is that the former Soviet Union's pipeline
network now spans 15 different republics, which have spent months locked in
dispute over questions such as pipeline ownership, maintenance and carriage
charges. Industrial action by any one of a number of republics or autonomous
republics and regions within Russia could damage Russia's ability to export
gas.
While attempts are being made to retain Gazprom as a Union-wide monopoly,
but as a joint-stock company in which almost all of the former Soviet
republics are likely to be partners, these may not be successful.
Mr James Ball, director of Gas Matters newsletter and a leading gas expert,
warns that 'the uncertainty about who will control gas exports in the longer
term may discourage foreign countries from signing new supply contracts.'
This could have a knock-on effect, by deterring western companies from
investing in Russia's upstream gas industry through fears they will be
unable to get the gas out.
With reserves of 3,300bn cubic metres, Algeria is in no position to
challenge Russia's role as principal external supplier to western Europe,
but last week's events might allow it to gain a somewhat larger share of the
market. Two factors work to Algeria's advantage. The first is that its
export routes go straight into European markets. The pipeline which carries
14bn cubic metres of gas annually to Italy, and whose capacity will double
by 1995, crosses Tunisia, a politically stable country, while 18bn cubic
metres travel by Liquefied Natural Gas (LNG) ships.
The second is that the country's well-run oil and gas monopoly, Sonatrach,
has already been through the process of deciding if and how foreign
companies are to work with it. Algeria has been lucky. The growth in demand
for its gas has exceeded Sonatrach's future capability, leading it to offer
far more rewarding terms for oil and gas exploration. This change of heart
in Algiers has led to the signing of a string of agreements with western
companies such as Total, Arco, Phillips Petroleum, Mobil, BP, Agip and
Cepsa. Current reserves figures are likely to prove conservative, given the
prolonged absence of internationally experienced explorers.
Meanwhile, the renovation and upgrading of existing LNG facilities is going
ahead, which will provide Sonatrach with extra capacity of 10bn cubic metres
at a cost of Dollars 2bn, which is substantially less than the cost of a
similar-size greenfield LNG project.
However, Sonatrach will still have a maximum annual export capacity of only
70bn cubic metres by 1997 and has indicated a desire to limit exports to
60bn cubic metres, 56bn of which is already sold. Strong market pressure
could encourage Algeria to sell all 70bn cubic metres.
There is another drawback: a political one. The Algerian government has been
mired in bloody confrontation with religious fundamentalists since it
cancelled last December's first ever multi-party elections. For Algeria's
buyers, there remains a fear of sabotage.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 4
</PAGE>
