<DATE>921029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / World Trade News: Daewoo Motor plans luxury car
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SEOUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DAEWOO Motor said yesterday it planned to produce a modified Korean version
of Honda's luxury car Legend by the end of 1993.
Mr Kim Woo-choong, Daewoo chairman, met Honda officials this week in Tokyo
to discuss details about the possible production of the Legend for the
Korean market.
Daewoo said yesterday it could not confirm whether a licensing agreement had
yet been signed.
Daewoo, South Korea's third largest car maker, would become the third
competitor in the country's luxury car market.
Hyundai has produced its top-of-the-range Grandeur since 1986, in
conjunction with Mitsubishi of Japan, while Kia Motors in May launched the
Potentia, which was developed in co-operation with Mazda, to compete against
the Grandeur.
Daewoo, an unlisted company, recorded an estimated loss of Won50bn (Pounds
37m) in the first half of this year and has an enormous debt/equity ratio of
over 2,000 per cent.
Daewoo last week formally ended its joint venture with General Motors by
buying the US carmaker's 50 per cent shareholding in the company for Dollars
170m. The joint venture ended because GM was concerned about Daewoo's
profitability.
Honda, Nissan and Suzuki of Japan have been mentioned as possible partners
with Daewoo in joint ventures. Daewoo already has a technical licensing
agreement with Nissan on compact cars.
</TEXT>
