<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 92 / World Trade News: Australia reconsiders ABB bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE State Energy Commission of Western Australia said yesterday it would
consider a revised proposal from Asea Brown Boveri (ABB), the Swiss/Swedish
engineering group, to develop a ADollars 2bn (Pounds 840m) power station.
ABB was commissioned in June to build and operate Australia's first
privately owned and funded power station at Collie, near a coalfield in
south-west Western Australia.
However, the project appeared close to collapse two weeks ago after the
state government indicated that it would not accept ABB's proposed
electricity prices, or its attempts to win state-government financial
support.
The group is believed to have reapproached the commission last week in a bid
to retain its sole-bidder status for the project.
The commission said the revised bid would be considered by a special board
meeting next week. However, it was not clear whether prices had been reduced
to a level acceptable to the state government.
</TEXT>
